	<item>
				<title>Protecting your online privacy with social network security settings</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/protecting-your-online-privacy-with-social-network-security-settings/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 21 Jun 2013 10:56:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094646</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740094659" alt="23snaps; Where are Facebook privacy settings" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/privacy-banner.jpg" width="640" height="216" />

The goal of social networking is to connect and communicate with a wide network of friends and family online, but it's imperative that you understand how to organize your privacy settings so as not to broadcast your personal information to the entire world. A lot of services provide default privacy settings that are basically wide open, this is because many free services can afford not to charge you as they make money by selling access to your information to various advertisers.*

Every network provides different privacy settings, and the ease of setting these depends on the individual service. For example, Twitter allows you to set your tweets to public or private - only one option that will then either allow the entire world to see what you have to say, or restrict access to  just those few that you choose to approve. Facebook is not as easy, their privacy settings allow you to make certain aspects of your profile private whilst sharing other things with a wider audience. You also have the option of sharing only with friends, with friends of friends, with people in specific groups and lists, or with everyone.

Whichever service you choose, you should be aware of what privacy options are available and whereabouts on the site the settings are located. If you have trouble finding this information you can usually contact the site owners for assistance or failing that, turn to Google. Points you should take into consideration are:
<ul>
	<li>Who can read your profile;</li>
	<li>Who can see your posts and activities;</li>
	<li>What information is shared with external sites and businesses;</li>
	<li>Which applications can access your data;</li>
	<li>What information your friends can share about you;</li>
	<li>Who can see your pictures and/or location;</li>
	<li>Which sites integrate with your social network.</li>
</ul>
Once you have adjusted your settings to provide the level of privacy you require, it is always worth reviewing whether they are working correctly. Disconnect from a friend or family member (you can reconnect with them straight after) and ask them to have a look at your profile and see what information is available to the general public. You'd be surprised how easy it is to miss something and inadvertently share more than you had intended.

Finally, make sure you are always aware of any changes to the privacy terms of the service you use. If the site does decide to alter their privacy settings, it may be necessary to re-set your own privacy specifications in order to keep your content secure. A good way to keep abreast of any changes would be to set up an email alert that concern changes to these terms, for example - Google will allow you to set up an alert for "Facebook changing their privacy settings". You will then receive an email containing any relevant information whenever it is posted either by Facebook or other interested third parties, as it is not guaranteed that the site themselves will make you aware.

<em>* Clarification - 23snaps is NOT one of the services that will sell access to you, the information and content your share on our service is private. We do not provide adjustable privacy settings because every account is private and secure.</em>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Does deleting a photo that you&#039;ve posted online actually remove it from the internet?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/does-deleting-a-photo-that-youve-posted-online-actually-remove-it-from-the-internet/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 28 Jun 2013 10:00:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094885</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/does-deleting-a-photo-that-youve-posted-online-actually-remove-it-from-the-internet/"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740094917" alt="23snaps; Deleting an online photo" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/23snaps-Deleting-a-photo.jpg" width="640" height="303" /></a>

&nbsp;

These days most people are aware that they need to be cautious when deciding what photos to post on the internet. Although it might seem like a good idea to share a particular image today, you may decide you want to delete it later, however once that photo is online it is actually very hard to remove it again.

If you tend to post your photos on a private platform, then you have a lot less to worry about. Depending on the service you use, there is a chance that once you delete an image or a video from your own account, it will still be stored in a server somewhere,  but the chance of it appearing to the public is minuscule. The problem tends to arise if you're publishing photos in a public space, such as a blog or forum. Websites and search engines store a cache of web pages in order to increase the speed of their service. Caching comes into action when you return to a web page you've looked at previously; instead of loading it from the original server your browser can get it from the cache, saving you time and the network the burden of some additional traffic. If your image was on a page that has been cached, deleting it from the original source will not necessarily prevent it from being returned when someone loads that page. Unfortunately there is little you can do to remove these pages from a cache, and as they can long outlast the original sites from which they were created, it means there is little you can do to prevent people from accessing your image.

The <a href="http://archive.org/web/web.php">Wayback Machine</a> is a website that allows you to browse through over 240 billion web pages archived from 1996 up to present day. A huge amount of those 240 billion web pages probably don't even exist at source anymore, but you can still access them without difficulty because they have been stored, unchanged, in various caches.

As with all online content, eventually it will become more obscure, more difficult to locate. Over 3 billion photos are uploaded to Facebook alone every day. This means that eventually a search will be unlikely to return your image, but it still doesn't mean you can be certain the image has completely disappeared. If you looked hard enough, you may still stumble across a cached page that contains your photo - so always think carefully before you post anything in a public space, as you may never be able to get it back.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Photo sharing etiquette - rules for sharing photos online.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/photo-sharing-etiquette-rules-for-sharing-photos-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 02 Jul 2013 12:01:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094924</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740094929" alt="23snaps; photography etiquette" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-photography-etiquette1.jpg" width="650" height="250" />

Almost everybody has the ability to take digital photos these days, what with smart phones, tablets and digital cameras. But what you need to remember is that even if you're totally snap happy, not everyone is going to a) want to be in your photos or b) want photos of themselves shared to a wider audience. Many parents are also concerned about photos of their children ending up online, and if they've spent days, months, or even years safeguarding their child's image, it really shouldn't be your decision to post a photo of their child where other people can see it.

In this digital age there are a few rules of etiquette that should be followed when it comes to sharing photos, although you might find them slightly restrictive, it's better to keep a photo to yourself rather than upset a friend or family member over a misjudged upload, right?

<em><strong>1. Don't assume people want to be photographed.</strong></em> Not everybody likes to have their photo taken, if you're going to an event, on a group outing, or just spending the day with friends or family, make people aware of your intentions to photograph them and give them the opportunity to opt out of being snapped.

<em><strong>2. </strong><strong><em>A</em>lways ask before posting.</strong></em> You might have been given the go-ahead to take the photos in the first place, but if you plan to share the photos online, ALWAYS ask first, especially when photos of children are involved.

<em><strong>3.</strong> <strong>Give people the option to tag themselves.</strong></em> It's usually best not to tag the photos you upload to the internet, but to let the people in those photos know they've been posted and give them the opportunity to tag themselves, if they choose to.

<strong><em>4. Avoid using kids' names</em></strong>. Even if you've gotten permission to share a child's photo online, it may not be OK to share that child's name. Some parents are uneasy about putting their child's name on the Internet, especially if it's searchable on Google. It's probably best to avoid using children's names in photo descriptions or comments.

<em><strong>5. What about if people forward your photos on?</strong></em> If you're particularly cautious about sharing photos online, make the people that you share them with aware of this. Let them know that they are one of a privileged few who have been given access to these photos, and you really don't want them shared any further. Also, give others the same courtesy, just because they've shared an image with you, it doesn't mean that they'll want you to share it on to your 1000+ Facebook friends.

<em><strong>6. Expect to be online!</strong></em> With the world and his wife owning some sort of photographic device, it's unlikely that you'll be able to prevent every image of you or your family from ever making it on to the internet. By making your friends and family aware that this is something you would rather avoid, you can most likely get away with very little exposure, perhaps just an untagged photo of the back of your child's head? It's inevitable that a photo will appear somewhere so learn to pick your battles, and don't panic if an unidentifiable photo makes it on to the internet every once in a while.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Childproof your internet browser</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/childproof-your-internet-browser/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 05 Jul 2013 14:00:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094933</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740094937" alt="23snaps; Childproofing your internet browser" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-Childproofing-your-internet-browser.jpg" width="640" height="299" />

The internet is full of websites that contain photos, videos and information you would rather your children didn't see. In order to preserve your little one's innocence without having to constantly peer over their shoulder, you can take steps to childproof your browser. There are lots of different ways to make browsing more child- friendly, few of which are mutually exclusive, the more you use the more confident you can be that inappropriate content can't slip through the net.

<strong>Web Filtering</strong>

You can enable web filtering on individual devices, but as most of these require an extension or plug-in, why not filter directly from the router? That way any device connected to your wi-fi will be subject to the same restrictions, and it will prevent your children from accidentally disabling any filter settings. <a href="http://www.opendns.com/home-solutions/parental-controls/">OpenDNS</a> has a free parental control package - OpenDNS Home allows you to tailor the filtering and security settings to suit your families specific needs.

The Internet's millions of websites are divided into various different categories that include things like "adult," "games," "academic fraud" and "social media." As a parent you can choose to block entire categories of content, or just block the individual websites that you know you don't want your family to access.

<strong>Enable in-built Family Safety Features in your device</strong>

Since the release of Vista, all copies of Windows include parental controls that allow you to control and monitor PC usage based on which account is signed in. These controls allow you to limit how long specific user accounts can be logged in on the PC, they also allow you to decide which programs and games can be run - depending on either their content rating or your individual opinions. It is also possible to view activity reports from the monitored accounts, to ensure you child hasn't accessed content that you deem inappropriate.

For Windows Vista and Windows 7 computers, you'll need to download the Family Safety application, which is a free component of the <a href="http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-live/essentials-other">Windows Essentials</a> software package, in order to alter your control settings. The Family Safety software is already built into Windows 8.

To enable and adjust Parental Controls settings just open <em>Parental Control</em> (<em>Family Safety</em> on Windows 8) from the start menu.

Mac users also have access to in-built control features. The most recent versions of Mac OS X, like Windows, will let you specify computer usage time limits for individual accounts. You can also identify which applications you are happy for that user account to run whilst preventing others from  being downloaded from the Apple App Store. Finally, Mac OS X will let you specify who the user can communicate with via the Mail, Messages and Game Center apps.

If you want to get started with parental controls on your Mac you just need to open the Apple menu in the top-left corner, click <em>System Preferences</em>, and in the System section, open <em>Parental Controls</em> (In OS X 10.7 and later, accounts with parental controls must be set as a ‘Managed with Parental Controls’ account).

<strong>Limit Wi-Fi availability</strong>

This step is fairly simple, turn off the wi-fi when you don't want your children surfing the web. Alternatively you can change the password daily, which will require your to children ask you before they can get online each day. Although this will in no way prevent them from viewing inappropriate content, you could make it a requirement of "internet time" that the kids are all in a communal space rather than hidden away in their bedrooms, which could discourage them from looking at sites that you'd rather they avoided.

<b>Enable Activity Logging on Your Router and PC</b>

Tech-savvy kids are probably aware that if they are looking at content they shouldn't be, they can delete the browser history or surf in a "private browsing" window such as Chrome's incognito window. However if you install monitoring software that is not easily defeated or detected by your child you can periodically review the log files to make sure your kids are only accessing suitable information. If you enable activity logging on your wireless router you will be able to view the logs from any devices connected to your wi-fi. There are various <a href="http://download.cnet.com/windows/monitoring-software/">free versions</a> of this type of software to choose from.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title> Don&#039;t give in to the fear of posting online</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/dont-give-in-to-the-fear-of-posting-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 09 Jul 2013 13:30:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094945</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[So many people are afraid to post their photos online for fear that someone they don't know will gain access to them, however it's extremely unlikely that your children or your family will ever come to any physical or emotional harm from a stranger discovering your photos online. Now, this doesn't mean that you should go ahead and post everything publicly without considering the possible consequences. Although the likelihood of somebody abusing your images is minuscule, it is still reasonable to take precautions to protect your privacy. This will then leave you safe in the knowledge that your friends and family can enjoy your photos without worrying who else can see them.

<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-39740094948" alt="23snaps; don't give in to the fear of posting online" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-dont-give-in-to-the-fear-of-posting-online.jpg" width="283" height="424" />

First and foremost, you should make sure that you <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-who-owns-the-photos-you-post-online/">understand the terms and conditions</a> of the service you plan to use to share your content. There are lots of sites out there that claim a <em>license to use</em> your image once it has been uploaded, which would then allow them to use it for advertising purposes or pass it on to third parties, should they choose to. But then there are also services, like 23snaps, that stake no claim on your photos whatsoever, so choose wisely.

Once you've picked the service that you think is right for you, it’s imperative that you're aware of how to <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/protecting-your-online-privacy-with-social-network-security-settings/">organize your privacy settings</a> so as not to broadcast your personal information to the entire world. A lot of services provide default privacy settings that are basically wide open, so you need to know what your settings are allowing people to see.

There are also other things you can do to help you feel secure about sharing your photos, such as <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-create-your-own-watermark-to-help-keep-your-photos-safe/">adding a watermark</a> to obviously display ownership of the images, and <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-geo-tagging-and-location-indicators/">disabling location tagging</a> to prevent people from determining where you live.

As long as you are careful about the service you use and the content of the photos your choose to share, there is no reason why you can't start posting your photos online with complete peace of mind.

Don't give in to your fear of sharing things online, the world is becoming a much more technological place and as long as you educate yourself about the ways in which to protect your privacy, there is no reason why you shouldn't be able to utilise some of the amazing services out there.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Does Snapkidz solve the issue with youngsters sharing inappropriate photos?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/does-snapkidz-solve-the-issue-with-youngsters-sharing-inappropriate-photos/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 16 Jul 2013 12:21:26 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094987</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740094992" alt="23snaps; Snapkidz" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Snapkidz1.jpg" width="640" height="299" />

Snapchat have recently launched an update that allows younger users, under the age of 13, to register for a more limited version of the app, which they've named SnapKidz.. Their information is not sent to Snapchat and no account is created.

The reason for this update is to allow youngsters to get involved with the app, whilst still complying with COPPA, which prevents the online collection of personal information from children under 13. The company said that "[Children] are able to use 'SnapKidz' a version of Snapchat that includes an interface for taking snaps, captioning, drawing, and saving them locally on the device, but does not support sending or receiving snaps or adding friends,"

<img class=" wp-image-39740094991 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 5px; " alt="23snaps; SnapKidz" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/snapkidz-2-150x150.jpg" width="175" height="175" />However, the appeal of Snapchat is not the ability to draw on and caption photos, it's the self destruct feature that naturally creates curiosity. Snapchat has no way of verifying the age of those registering for the service which means there is nothing to prevent younger children from claiming to be older in order to gain access to the full version rather than the restricted kids' version. Even if your children do play by the rules and stick to SnapKidz if they're under 13 years of age, if they are at all tech-savvy they will probably be aware that they still have access to the internet, and as the snaps are saved to the device’s camera-roll they could still be shared quite easily, either by uploading them to a social network or sending on via email. It appears that there aren't any particularly secure barriers that will prevent the sharing of photos should your child want to do so, SnapKidz just seems like a way to get more people using the app, so that as the children turn 13 there will be more accounts registered.

Nonetheless, if your child is desperate to try SnapKidz you could download the app and register for them, to ensure the correct age is entered. Then disable any internet access on the device to prevent them from breaking out of the sandbox.]]></content:encoded>

				<title>Would you make your child sign an online etiquette agreement?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/would-you-make-your-child-sign-an-online-etiquette-agreement/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 18 Jul 2013 10:20:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095011</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-39740095016 alignright" alt="23snaps: Online Ettiquete Agreement 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/1059067259_cd6aca5fb5-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" />Our children are what will be referred to as "Digital Natives" because they have been born into an age that is so thoroughly saturated with technology.  Learning to use the digital devices that are so readily available is likely to occur as early on in life as learning to walk and talk. As children are beginning to interact online at a younger age, it becomes increasingly important to ensure they understand both an appropriate way to conduct their behaviour online and the possible dangers and pitfalls that lurk out there on the internet.

One way that many parents are targeting this is to draw up an online etiquette agreement, this contract would then outline the rules and regulations that the parents feel their children should follow in order to earn their internet usage.  It is our advice that a contract such as this should be less about punishing infringements and more about helping your children to understand the importance of making safe and sensible choices when they're online. You can also put your mind at ease by checking your child's knowledge and understanding of what would constitute responsible internet use.

Would you use a contract of this type? If so, we have developed an <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/OnlineEtiquetteAgreement-1.pdf">example contract</a> that would be appropriate for children aged around 8-12 years old. Please feel free to print it off and use it with your family.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/OnlineEtiquetteAgreement-1.pdf"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740095012" alt="23snaps Online Ettiquette Agreement" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-Online-Ettiquette-Agreement.png" width="596" height="767" />

</a>]]></content:encoded>

				<title>The World Celebrates the Birth Announcement of the New Prince of Cambridge</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/the-world-celebrates-the-birth-announcement-of-the-new-prince-of-cambridge/</link>

		<description></description>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Trafalgar-Square1.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095050" alt="Trafalgar Square" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Trafalgar-Square1-150x150.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/CN-Tower.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095048" alt="CN Tower" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/CN-Tower-150x150.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Niagara-Falls1.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095049" alt="Niagara Falls" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Niagara-Falls1-150x150.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a>

</em><strong>Trafalgar Square                               CN Tower                                                Niagara Falls</strong>

They were all there to see the proclamation announcing the birth, signed by the royal doctors, displayed on an easel in the Palace forecourt.

We would just like to wish our future Monarch and his parents our warmest wishes. And you know where to <a href="http://23snaps.com">find us</a> if you want to get your 23snaps account up and running!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>How to Pack a Punch Using Filters On Your Photos</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/how-to-pack-a-punch-using-filters-on-your-photos/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 24 Jul 2013 11:02:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095104</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Photo sharing has become a huge part of today’s social culture. Instagram, Facebook, 23snaps; all of these platforms are used on a daily basis by thousands of people in order to do one thing - share photos.  This is highlighted by the fact that the total number of photos shared online by Instagram users alone is approximately 40 million photos a day, that is a staggering amount! If you love to share beautiful photos, whether they feature babies, architecture, food, or nature, it’s likely that you have had the opportunity to make use of various photo filters. The big problem is … which one to choose? There are so many options out there! We wanted to give you a little advice on which filters might work best for the style you were hoping to create. As we’ve just launched our new Instagram auto-post feature, we thought we’d talk you through some of the best ways to use Instagram’s most popular filters on photos of your children.

When taking a photo of a baby or smaller child, one of the most important factors is catching the right moment; they could be asleep or playing alone, but your best bet is to catch them when their already occupied. You should also look to include some cute details, such as their tiny fingers or chubby feet. Finally, don’t be afraid to get down to their eye-level, it might not be comfy lying down on your belly, camera in hand, but from that angle you have a much better chance of getting a beautiful shot. Besides, these images will become priceless to you in the future, so what’s a little hard work right now?

Now, if you’re planning to share these photos of your kids, you might be considering using filters, to ensure the photos pack a punch.

One very popular Instagram filter is <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Amaro.png"><em><strong>Amaro</strong></em></a>, this adds some extra light to the photo, making it the perfect choice for darker images. Applying this filter would also give your photos a slightly vintage look. <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Earlybird.png"><b><i>Earlybird</i></b></a>, just like Amaro, would create a retro effect in your photos, which is very much on trend, by using this filter you would produce a sepia effect. Another of the best filters to use in order to create an aged look is <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Valencia.png"><b><i>Valencia</i></b></a>, but this is better used for colorful, brighter photos.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Amaro.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095105" alt="Amaro" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Amaro-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Earlybird.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095106" alt="Earlybird" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Earlybird-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Valencia.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095114" alt="Valencia" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Valencia-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>
<em>                    Amaro                                              Earlybird                                          Valencia</em>

For a portrait of your child, <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Rise.png"><b><i>Rise</i></b></a> would be perfect filter. It adds a golden glow and soft tones to photos, which works incredibly well with the dewy texture of a child’s skin tone. If your kids are outside in the sunshine, or relaxing with your loved ones on a warm summer evening, then a filter like <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Toaster.png"><b><i>Toaster</i></b></a> would be perfect. Just like Rise, Toaster uses a strong red tint to add glow and warmth to photos, which makes a good effect when combined with an image of a beautiful summer evening.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Rise.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095110" alt="Rise" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Rise-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Toaster.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095113" alt="Toaster" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Toaster-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>
<em>                       Rise                                                 Toaster</em>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hudson.png"><b><i>Hudson</i></b></a> is well suited for photos of colorful buildings, and architecture in general, as it gives an effect of cold tint, dodged center and shadows. These effects help emphasize the light of the photo whilst also making it cooler and would work well for most outdoor images where your child was not the sole focus. <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sierra.png"><b><i>Sierra </i></b></a>is also a good filter for outdoor use, although its effects are different to Hudson as it produces more warmth. <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sutro.png"><b><i>Sutro</i></b></a> is another that is excellent for outdoors spaces; it specifically highlights purple and brown tones, which could create a fantastic horror effect for Halloween.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hudson.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095108" alt="Hudson" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hudson-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sierra.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095111" alt="Sierra" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sierra-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sutro.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095112" alt="Sutro" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Sutro-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>
<em>                    Hudson                                                Sierra                                                  Sutro</em>

The most frequently used Instagram filter is <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Lo-Fi.png"><b><i>Lo-Fi</i></b></a>, which boosts contrast and brings out warm tones. It was designed for use with food, and seeing as one of the most popular photo subjects for people to share on Instagram is what they’re eating, it’s no surprise this is one of the most commonly used filters. However, the rich warm tones also work fantastically well with photos of young children, especially autumnal photos, where the world is already full of such contrast. <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hefe.png"><b><i>Hefe</i></b></a> is very similar to Lo-fi, it is just a bit softer, and so it can be used in the same circumstances as Lo-fi.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Lo-Fi.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095109" alt="Lo-Fi" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Lo-Fi-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>     <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hefe.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095107" alt="Hefe" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Hefe-168x300.png" width="168" height="300" /></a>
<em>                        Lo-Fi                                                  Hefe</em>

Really, the choice of which filter to use is down to one’s preference, however these filters have been deigned to suit a certain type of image. Knowing which one to use, and what effect it will create, will go a long way to improving your photos.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Backlogging content</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 26 Jul 2013 09:09:30 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095133</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[As we've been adding more and more exciting features to 23snaps, we've realised that our users may be forgetting about some of the much loved features that they might not have used in a while. So, we've decided to start a weekly post containing tips and hacks for getting the most out of your 23snaps app. We know there are plenty of features that you'd like to see us develop in the future, but there may be a way right now that you can get the results you want with a simple little trick - and we're gonna show you how! If there is anything you'd like tips or advice on, or think we should include in our weekly post, feel free to leave a comment here on the blog or drop us a line at <a href="mailto:support@23snaps.com">support(at)23snaps(dot)com</a> using the subject line “Tip of the Week”.

This week we wanted to help you with back-logging content for your child(ren). We know that a lot of our users were lucky enough to have come across the app in the very early days of becoming parents, which allowed them to build their child's timeline from the very beginning. But what happens if your son or daughter was a year or two old when you downloaded 23snaps? Should you not also be able to have a complete timeline of your child's life? Well the answer is YES! Of course you should, and you can.

<img class=" wp-image-39740095140 alignright" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Screen-Shot-2013-07-25-at-14.09.39-297x300.png" alt="23snaps" width="208" height="210" />

We know that only being able to upload one photo at a time from the app is frustrating, especially if you have a couple of years worth of photos you want to upload ... you could be there forever! Rest assured, our development team are hard at work developing this feature for use in the mobile app, but at this time it is actually possible to post multiple photos to your child's timeline in one go on the 23snaps website. AND, assuming you haven't modified the images since they were taken, the website will automatically recognise the timestamp embedded in the photo and upload it to the correct point in the timeline.

All you have to do is:

1. <a href="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/entries/24602486-Getting-started-with-23snaps#add_child">Create a profile for your child</a>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Backlogging-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-39740095136" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Backlogging-1-1024x539.jpg" alt="Back dating content" width="640" height="336" /></a>

2. <a href="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/entries/24639316-Uploading-content-to-23snaps#batch_uploading">Batch upload</a> multiple photos and videos to populate your child's timeline

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Screen-Shot-2013-07-25-at-12.25.33.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-39740095137" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Screen-Shot-2013-07-25-at-12.25.33-1024x537.png" alt="Back dating content 2" width="640" height="335" /></a>

3. Ensure the dates are correct to allow us to place them accurately in chronological order

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Screen-Shot-2013-07-25-at-12.27.54.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-39740095138" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Screen-Shot-2013-07-25-at-12.27.54-1024x536.png" alt="Back dating content 3" width="640" height="335" /></a>

&nbsp;

The amount of photos you can post in one batch depends on the strength of your internet connection, but we would recommend starting off with about 10 at a time, and if all seems hunky dory, you can increase that number as you go along. Remember, each photo can be no bigger than 10mb, but if you do accidentally include a bigger one, just click Try Again and add a different photo in it's place, the smaller images will have already been uploaded.

If you'd like step-by-step instructions on how to upload multiple photos on the web, you can find them (and some handy screenshots) right <a href="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/entries/24639316-Uploading-content-to-23snaps#batch_uploading">here</a>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>How often do you change your online passwords?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/how-often-do-you-change-your-online-passwords/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 30 Jul 2013 13:48:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095154</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Password-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095161" alt="Password 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Password-2.jpg" width="640" height="400" /></a>

Did you know that of all the thousands of combinations available to us, the most common 4 digit pin that people use is <a href="http://www.datagenetics.com/blog/september32012/">1234</a>? Or that approximately <a href="https://www.paypal-media.com/assets/pdf/fact_sheet/cis_paypal_whitepaper_final.pdf">60%</a> of us use the exact same password for every single account that we have registered in our name? It seems that we're almost asking for someone to breach our privacy!

Even more surprising is the fact that <a href="http://passwordresearch.com/stats/study89.html">34%</a> of the people asked had never changed their passwords. <em>Never! </em>

We understand that it's really easy to get stuck using the same password for months and months, or even years, once you have it memorised, and you may not really want to revise it, but it really is a good idea to change your password periodically. Ideally you should change it at least every three months. There are several reasons for this; first of all, the most common way for a hacker to figure out your password is by using what's known as a "brute force" attack. This is when a computer program is employed to attempt every possible password combination, until eventually it breaks into your account. Luckily most online accounts have systems in place to prevent this form of attack. Services that provide access to such accounts will cut off access attempts and ban IP addresses that attempt to log in too many times. However, if you use the same password across the board and someone deciphers it on one platform, they could then use it to gain access elsewhere, there-by outsmarting those services that would have otherwise prevented the brute force attack. Therefore, by regularly changing your password, you can more effectively protect all of your accounts.

<img class=" wp-image-39740095163 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 5px; margin-bottom: 5px;" alt="Password 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Password-1-300x270.jpg" width="249" height="225" />

&nbsp;

Secondly, if passwords are successfully stolen without the knowledge of the owner, those passwords wouldn't necessarily be used immediately. They could be collected and saved for future use, or sold on, and you would be none the wiser. So, even if your password had been discovered, if you apply the good practise of changing your password regularly, you could be lucky enough to change it before anybody has an opportunity to use it.

&nbsp;

We know it can be time-consuming and frustrating trying to think of (and remember) a new password on a regular basis, especially one that would be considered acceptably strong enough to provide good protection against a brute force attack. A great way to create and memorise a new password every few months is to use a password generator to create a random string of 8 characters, including letters, numbers and symbols, which you can write down and store in your purse or diary. Use that string of characters combined with a memorable word of your choosing to create your new password. That way, you will have created an incredibly strong password containing 12+ characters that would be very difficult for someone to guess.

&nbsp;

Finally, we'd just like to advise you that it's wise never to use a word or phrase that could be easily guessed by someone who has access to very little information about you. For example, if your email address was John.Smith85@mail.com, you'd be unwise to use any part of your name or date of birth to create your password. In this case, just by gaining access to your email address (which is likely to be fairly public) someone would also find out your full name and year of birth, so be careful about the memorable info you use to create your password. Our recommendation? M<em>emorable</em> but <em>obscure</em>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Perfect Wallpaper</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-perfect-wallpaper/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 02 Aug 2013 11:30:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095182</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[On the iOS and Android apps, you have the ability to set a wallpaper image at the top of your child's timeline. On the <em><strong><a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_wallpaper">23snaps website</a></strong></em>, you also have the option to set a family wallpaper, that will head up the timeline containing all of your family's content. This wallpaper will also act as yours (and your partners) wallpaper.

So you've found the perfect image and you want to set it to your page.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/hols-steps_1574622a.jpeg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095185" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/hols-steps_1574622a-300x199.jpeg" alt="23snaps Wallpaper 2" width="300" height="199" /></a>

At this time, it is not possible to edit your wallpaper image on the web, which unfortunately means you could be stuck with an image that looks like this:

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Picture-5.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095187" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Picture-5.png" alt="23snaps Wallpaper 1" width="640" /></a>

But don't despair! We have a great trick to help you set the perfect wallpaper.

You will need some image editing software, if you don't already have photoshop (or something similar), we'd recommend <a href="http://www.gimp.org/downloads/">GIMP</a>; it's completely free and very easy to use. What you need to do is open your image in the editing program and crop it to 940 x 250 pixels, making sure that your favorite part of the image remains. You will then need to export it as a .JPEG file and save it to your computer. Now, upload it as you wallpaper on 23snaps, as it will be sized to fit exactly, you can be sure that you will have a perfect wallpaper to complete your family page.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Picture-3.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095186" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Picture-3.png" alt="23snap Wallpaper 3" width="640" /></a>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>39740095182</wp:post_id>

	<item>
				<title>What are the advantages to sharing photos privately?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/what-are-the-advantages-to-sharing-photos-privately/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 31 Jul 2013 12:52:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095192</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-share-privately-2.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095194" alt="23snaps share privately 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-share-privately-2.png" width="640" /></a>

There are a lot of valid reasons to restrict your photo sharing to a private network. By keeping your images out of the public eye you are more easily able to manage who gets to see them, and have better control over where they may end up.

There are various public platforms upon which you can share photos, and in order to use these services you must first agree to their terms and conditions. A lot of these photo sharing sites state that by uploading an image you are giving them <em>license to use</em> it. This means that whilst you do still own the photo, the sharing site has the right to use it in its promotional activities, and it can transfer or sub-license that right to its partners. This means you could unwittingly become the face of a brand or service, for which you would not be compensated, and there's very little you could do about it. Sharing your photos in a private space will reduce the likelihood of encountering terms that apply licenses such as this.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-sharing-privately.jpeg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095195" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 5px; margin-bottom: 5px;" alt="23snaps sharing privately" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/23snaps-sharing-privately-150x150.jpeg" width="165" height="165" /></a>Keeping your photos private can also help you to protect your own, and your family's, safety in real life. It is sad to say that some people will take advantage of the information they glean from your images and use it to identify or locate you. Although this happening is incredibly unlikely, it is possible.  So whilst taking a photo of a street name or landmark is great for when you’re looking back and reminiscing about the places you’ve visited, it may be less wise to include the name of your own road or your child’s school, <em>unless</em> you plan to share the images privately. Otherwise it could make it incredibly simple for someone to track you or your family down should they be so inclined.

Another issue concerning publishing photos in a public space is that you can never truly delete them. Websites and search engines store a cache of web pages in order to increase the speed of their service. Caching comes into action when you return to a web page you’ve looked at previously; instead of loading it from the original server, your browser can get it from the cache, saving you time and the network the burden of some additional traffic. If your image was on a page that has been cached, deleting it from the original source will not necessarily prevent it from being returned when someone loads that page. Unfortunately there is little you can do to remove these pages from a cache, and they can long outlast the original sites from which they were created, which means there is little you can do to prevent people from accessing an image that you shared publicly, even long after it's been "deleted". By keeping your images to a private platform, you exponentially reduce the chance of your images being cached, as the crawlers that find the pages that are stored, are unable to access your images.

The choice of where to share is yours and yours alone, but we definitely think the advantages of sharing privately win out, which is why we created 23snaps!]]></content:encoded>

				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Exporting your data</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/tip-of-the-week-exporting-your-data/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 09 Aug 2013 10:25:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095235</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We've just launched a new feature that will allow you to export all of the photos and videos that have been uploaded to your 23snaps account by yourself and your partner (where applicable). For whatever reason, if you need to download a copy of all of your content - now you can, and the process is so simple!

You'll need to log on to your account via the <em><strong><a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_exportdata">23snaps website</a></strong></em>, then just click on <em>"Your Name"</em> in the menu bar at the top of the screen. From the dropdown menu select <em>Settings</em>.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/tpoxgofxutmc5wz/?name=Export+data+1.jpg" alt="Export_data_1.jpg" width="500" />

Now click on the <em>Account</em> tab.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/zkebqrlwvcybtpo/?name=Export+data+2.jpg" alt="Export_data_2.jpg" width="500" />

At the bottom of the page there is an option to <em>Export Your Family Data</em>. We will then prepare your data to be exported.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/wryc4qyuqei29rq/?name=Export+data+3.jpg" alt="Export_data_3.jpg" width="500" />

&nbsp;

When the data is ready, you will receive an email containing a link; from which you can download your data. Please be aware that this link will only be valid for 24hours. By clicking on the link you will begin the download of a .zip file that will contain every photo and video uploaded to your family's 23snaps account.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/p3qwzmjzww007xf/?name=Screen+Shot+2013-08-01+at+10.59.28.png" alt="Screen_Shot_2013-08-01_at_10.59.28.png" width="500" />]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>What kind of photo sharer are you?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/what-kind-of-photo-sharer-are-you/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 08 Aug 2013 10:49:32 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095247</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Oversharer</em></strong></p>
<em><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/over-sharer.png"><img class="wp-image-39740095253 alignright" style="margin-bottom: 10px; margin-right: 10px;" alt="23snaps; Oversharer" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/over-sharer-300x225.png" width="267" height="200" /></a></em>
<p dir="ltr">Do you share every single moment of your child’s life? If you see an unusual shape or color in a dirty diaper, is your first instinct to post it to Facebook? Then you are an oversharer. As much as your little bundle of joy may be the most amazing thing you have ever seen, it doesn’t necessarily mean that the rest of the world will feel the same way. However, if sharing every single photo you snap makes you happy, then don’t let other people stop you! Although it might be a good idea to share those photos with a smaller circle of friends and family … maybe just the ones who will appreciate it? Add them all on 23snaps and share to your heart’s content.</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Filter Fanatic</em></strong></p>
<em><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/IMG_20130808_111850.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095252" style="margin-bottom: 10px; margin-right: 10px;" alt="Filter Fanatic" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/IMG_20130808_111850-300x300.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a></em>
<p dir="ltr">Does everything look better with a filter? Does a vignette make your image pop? If you can’t resist running every photo through that edit process then you’re a filter fanatic. Filters can really make or break a photo, so it’s a good idea to figure out which ones work best for your needs. Did you know that each filter is designed for a specific type of photo? <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/how-to-pack-a-punch-using-filters-on-your-photos/">We did!</a> Although there is absolutely nothing wrong with loving a good filter, it’s worth keeping in mind that if you plan to print your photos, the filters can reduce the quality, so it’s a good idea to keep the original, unedited versions too!</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Story-Teller</em></strong></p>
 <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Once-upon-a-time.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-39740095249 alignright" style="margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;" alt="23snaps; Story-Teller" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Once-upon-a-time-300x199.jpg" width="226" height="150" /></a>Do you think long and hard about which photo should be shared next? Is it important to retain the chronologyand accuracy of the timeline your building? Then you’re a story-teller. You use photo sharing as a medium to tell your child’s story in a carefully orchestrated manner. This is a great way of building a __ of your precious memories, but don’t forget, there are ways to make this easier! 23snaps automatically recognises the timestamp embedded in your photos, so regardless of when you post them, they will always appear at the right point in your timeline.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Shy Sharer</em></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-08-at-11.20.39.png"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-39740095250" style="margin-bottom: 10px; margin-right: 10px;" alt="23snaps; shy sharer" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-08-at-11.20.39-300x194.png" width="300" height="194" /></a>Only post a photo once a week, or maybe only once a month? If you post infrequently because you’re unsure of whether people are interested in your photos then you’re a shy sharer. If you post in this way because it makes you happy, then just keep at it, but if you’d like to post more regularly then don’t worry about what other people think … you should share as often as makes you happy. More often than not, people will be delighted that you’ve chosen to share your precious moments with them!</p>
&nbsp;
<div dir="ltr"><strong><em>Snap-Happy</em></strong></div>
<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/7333055-a-pile-of-photographs-arranged-into-a-background.jpg"><img class="wp-image-39740095248 alignright" alt="23snaps; snap happy" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/7333055-a-pile-of-photographs-arranged-into-a-background-300x300.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a>If you post numerous shots of the same scene, or over a hundred snaps from the same event, then you’re snap-happy! It’s often necessary to take loads of photos to get that one stella shot, but you might want to have a sort through and pick a few favorites before you share, otherwise you run the risk of those really amazing photos get lost among the crowd.</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Re-sharer</em></strong></p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-08-at-11.24.49.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095251" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;" alt="23snaps; re-sharer" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-08-at-11.24.49-300x292.png" width="210" height="204" /></a>Do you only re-share other people’s content? Maybe you’re a grandparent, or an aunt or uncle, who can’t resist showing those cute photos off to a wider circle. Although many people would be flattered by this behaviour, it’s always wise to check with the original poster to make sure they’re happy with their photos going out to a bigger audience.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Do smartphone photos pose a risk to your privacy?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/do-smartphone-photos-pose-a-risk-to-your-privacy/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 14 Aug 2013 15:40:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095314</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[So if you've been on Twitter at all in the last 48 hours you can't have missed the new wave of worry about the geo-tagging that occurs in a digital photo's metadata when taken on a smartphone. There are a massive amount of people out there who can't resist the instant gratification that comes with posting a photo to Facebook or Instagram whilst enjoying a day out/meal/party/event ..... the list goes on. But if you're taking most of your photos at home, how comfortable are you with the idea of someone being able to pinpoint your address on a map? Apparently some service provide this feature! Obviously the intention would not be to aid in any sort of suspicious activities, but there are people that might abuse this type of feature, and that's what you want to avoid.

Instagram, for example, adds all of your photos to a "Photo Map", pinpointing exactly where they were taken, and if it's obvious the images capture scenes inside your home, it's not all that difficult to put 2 and 2 together.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/new-instagram-app-map.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-39740095316 alignnone" alt="Instagram Photo Map" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/new-instagram-app-map-300x220.jpg" width="300" height="220" /></a>

Facebook also has a similar feature, which will add any of the events you post, or are tagged in, to the "Places" map. The default setting on Facebook is to include this information, unless you choose to disable it.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-14-at-16.23.01.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-39740095315 alignnone" alt="Facebook &quot;Places&quot;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-08-14-at-16.23.01-300x220.png" width="300" height="220" /></a>

However, there is absolutely no reason to worry, it is no easy to control the exposure of this information, you just need to know how. First you need to understand what geo-tagging is; it is the process of adding geographical identification metadata to your media, including photographs and videos. In simple terms, when you take a photo the camera grabs your location information from your device's GPS system and records that information in the background of your photo. If you want to avoid sharing this information online, you can choose to either turn off the GPS on your phone altogether, which will automatically prevent the photo from being tagged with a location because it wouldn’t be able to detect it’s own position, or if you don’t want to lose the ability to use your phone’s inbuilt GPS altogether, you can usually go into the general settings and turn off the location services for individual apps. To manage either of these options on an iOS device, you need to click Settings&gt;Privacy&gt;Location Services and either disable the GPS entirely or manually turn off the permission for each app you wish to prevent from posting this information.

Digital photos have always included large amounts of meta-information, and smart phones and devices have taken this information and made a much better use of it. The problem is not necessarily that the images include this information, but what is done with it by the service you use to share your photos. As long as the geo-location information in not publicly displayed in a way that you were not expecting, you don’t need to panic about the fact that the information exists in the file.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Posting Multiple Photos at One Time</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/tip-of-the-week-posting-multiple-photos-at-one-time/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Aug 2013 11:00:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095328</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We've had a lot of users writing in recently to request a feature that will allow them to <em><strong>post multiple photos</strong></em> to their 23snaps account in one go, rather than having to post every photo individually. Our development team are working hard to create this feature in both the iOS and Android versions of the app for you, and we hope to be able to release it soon. In the meantime, this feature does already exist on the<em><strong> <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_multiplephotos">23snaps website</a></strong></em>, so we thought this week we'd walk you through how to use it.

Once you're logged into your 23snaps account on the website, click on the orange <em><strong>+</strong> Post</em> button in the top right corner of the screen,

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/vpnsi1ypw3kfqxg/?name=Batch+upload+1.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_1.jpg" width="338" height="212" />

Select the <em>Photo</em> option.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/vrdj3ebqrur6xfv/?name=Batch+upload+2.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_2.jpg" width="338" height="212" />

Then click <em>Select Files. </em>

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/xpcgoab2v8uzkhf/?name=Batch+upload+3.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_3.jpg" width="338" height="212" />

From the list on the left of the lightbox, select the option from which you would like to upload your images and click C<em>hoose File. </em>

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/ojamninilgxautm/?name=Batch+upload+4.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_4.jpg" width="338" height="212" />

Holding the shift key on your keyboard, select all of the photos you wish to upload and click <em>Open. </em>

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/zftpa2tlosit4rd/?name=Batch+upload+5.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_5.jpg" width="338" height="212" />

Now you will have the option to individually alter the dates, tags and descriptions for each photo. When you are ready to upload, click <em>Submit Photos </em>at the bottom of the screen.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/cht401kioixiz23/?name=Batch+upload+6.jpg" alt="Batch_upload_6.jpg" width="338" height="211" />

Hope that helps! But if you have any trouble utilising this feature, you can drop us a line any time at <a href="mailto:support@23snaps.com">support(at)23snaps(dot)com</a>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Should your child have a tablet?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/should-your-child-have-a-tablet/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Aug 2013 14:22:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095336</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Best-Android-Tablets-For-Kids1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-39740095349 alignnone" alt="23snaps; should your child have a tablet?" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Best-Android-Tablets-For-Kids1.jpg" width="749" height="319" /></a>

Chances are, if your child sees you using your tablet regularly, it won't be long until they want one of their own. But the question is ... should your child own their own tablet? The answer for each family will inevitably be different, there is no hard and fast rule as to whether children should be allowed their own devices, or at what age they should get one. However, lots of parents are concerned about whether they should supply their children with the latest technology, so we thought we'd offer our advice.

In the increasingly digital environment that we live in, children are being exposed to technology at a far earlier age than any other generation ever has. Luckily, there are lots of companies out their that have designed devices specifically for younger children, such as the <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/LeapFrog-LeapPad2-Explorer-Tablet-Green/dp/B0089RPUHO/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917228&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=leappad+2">Leap Frog LeapPad</a>, <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Nabi-Kids-Inch-Android-Tablet/dp/B008DBI5RI/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917198&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=fuhu+nabi+2">Fuhu Nabi</a> and <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/VTech-136853-Vtech-InnoTab-Pink/dp/B00763PSGU/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917264&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=innotab+2">VTech Innotab</a>. If you are planning on getting your young child their own tablet we would definitely recommend starting out with one of these, as opposed to an iPad or Nexus, as they allow your child to become accustomed to using the device, without the possibility of accessing the internet or any age inappropriate apps. They are also far cheaper, and we all know that an expensive "toy" in the hands of a small child is not the most sensible combination.

<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/LeapFrog-LeapPad2-Explorer-Tablet-Green/dp/B0089RPUHO/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917228&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=leappad+2"><img class=" wp-image-39740095345 alignnone" alt="23snaps; Leap Pad 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/LeapPad2-Green-front-240x300.jpg" width="150" /></a>    <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Nabi-Kids-Inch-Android-Tablet/dp/B008DBI5RI/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917198&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=fuhu+nabi+2"><img class=" wp-image-39740095343 alignnone" style="color: #333333;" alt="23snaps; Fuhu Nabi 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Fuhu-Nabi-2-300x210.jpg" height="150" /></a>      <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/VTech-136853-Vtech-InnoTab-Pink/dp/B00763PSGU/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1376917264&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=innotab+2"><img class=" wp-image-39740095344 alignnone" alt="23snaps; Innotab 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Innotab-2-Blue-Front-FINAL-high-res-236x300.jpg" width="150" /></a>

You should also be wary of whether your child will have the strength of will to put down their device should you choose to give them one, as it's unwise to allow kids to stare at a screen for hours and hours on end. Although there is no conclusive study yet on the long term effects of children using tablets, the <a href="http://www.aap.org/en-us/advocacy-and-policy/aap-health-initiatives/Pages/Media-and-Children.aspx">AAP</a> recommends that children under the age of 2 should have absolutely no screen time, this is because "a child's brain develops rapidly during these first years, and young children learn best by interacting with people, not screens". Therefore it would be unwise for a child of this age to have any access to a tablet, let alone own their own. The AAP also advise that children over the age of 2 should be limited to no more than 2 hours of screen time a day. Assuming that your child has access to their own device, it would most likely make it much harder to enforce this time limit compared to them sharing a tablet with other family members. If you are concerned about your children spending too much time on electronic devices just remember that it will be up to you as a parent to set, and enforce, the ground rules for using the device.

That being said, a tablet is a device that can help your child learn important skills - like writing letters or counting for toddlers or multiplication and problem solving for older children. It is also fairly safe to assume that the use of tech devices such as these will become the norm in education, and allowing your child to get used to using a tablet outside of school will undoubtably assist them when it comes to using them in a classroom.

There are definitely pros and cons in this argument, but assuming that you can afford to purchase a tablet for your child, then we think it'll be a great learning experience for them. Just be prepared to monitor their usage and activity, and remember that an electronic device is no substitute for playing outside and interacting with other people.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Is it safe to post photos of your children online?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/is-it-safe-to-post-photos-of-you-children-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 21 Aug 2013 15:01:23 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095368</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/23snaps-Watermark-After.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-39740094368 alignright" style="margin-left: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;" alt="23snaps; protect children" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/23snaps-Watermark-After.jpg" width="259" height="346" /></a>

As a parent, <strong>keeping your children safe</strong> is your primary concern. The debate about whether posting baby photos online is sensible, and safe, has been going onfor years and there is no definitive answer. However there are ways to <strong>reduce the risks</strong> that could occur as a result of sharing photos, and to protect children in said photos.

When people think of the dangers of posting photos of children on the internet, the most common concern is that someone of unpleasant nature may try to use the images to stalk your child. Although this is a valid concern, the likelihood of anyone using your images in this way is practically non-existent. The bigger issue is the ability people have to <strong>download the images</strong> that you post. Although it is much more likely that the only people who would take advantage of this would be friends and family who just want copies of the images for themselves, it is not unheard of for people to abuse this ability for less savoury purposes.

There is also a chance that other <strong>people may "borrow" your photos</strong> in order to a) try and pass them off as there own or b) use them for promotional activities such as marketing and advertising. In 2009 a <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-205_162-3290986.html">teenage girl from Texas</a> was dismayed to discover that her image, that had been posted to a friends Flikr account, wound up on an ad for Virgin Mobile in Australia.

If any of these possible outcomes make you uncomfortable; you have a couple of choices. You can choose to completely refrain from posting any images online, or you can use a service that will allow you to share your photos privately to prevent any unauthorised persons from gaining access to them.

Regardless of where you choose to share your photos, there are some extra precautions you can take to protect your photos, and your children.

- Never add a photo to a public site without<strong> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-create-your-own-watermark-to-help-keep-your-photos-safe/">adding a watermark</a></strong> to it first. This is much easier than it sounds, and it will prevent anyone from using your image for commercial purposes.

- Always, always, <strong>always read the Terms and Conditions</strong> of the site you plan to use. One of the most common lies on the web is "I have read and agree to the terms and conditions". Be careful not to fall into this trap, by putting a tick in that little box, you could be giving someone else <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-who-owns-the-photos-you-post-online/">rights to your photos</a>.

- If you are sharing your photos with a small and private group, <strong>add a comment or a tag with express instructions</strong> on how you would like the image to be treated. For example "I hope you enjoy the photo, but please do not share, save or redistribute it in any way".

If you go about it in an educated and responsible manner, there is no reason why posting photos of your children online cannot be perfectly safe. And our final piece of advice? <strong>Use <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=safe">23snaps</a> to share your baby photos</strong>. It's free, private and so simple to use. What more could you want?]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Post to Facebook</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/tip-of-the-week-post-to-facebook/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 23 Aug 2013 11:30:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095376</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[23snaps is perfect for <strong>private photo sharing</strong> and building a <strong>family photo gallery</strong>, but occasionally there might be a particular photo you want to post to Facebook for a larger audience to enjoy. This is why we have created our <strong><a href="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/entries/24646528-Sharing-your-23snaps-content-via-email-and-Facebook#share_to_FB">Share to Facebook</a></strong> feature, it will allow you to simultaneously upload your photo to 23snaps and to a Facebook album titled <em>23snaps.</em>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Share-to-FB-album.jpg"><img class="alignright  wp-image-39740095377" style="margin-left: 20px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Share-to-FB-album-200x300.jpg" alt="Share to FB - album" width="225" height="340" /></a>This feature is<strong> already available</strong> on the <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=blog&amp;c=TOTW">iPhone and iPad</a> version of 23snaps, and we a so very close to releasing it for our <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/com.snaps23.android?pid=blog&amp;c=TOTW">Android</a> users too ... so look out for any updates!

To make use of this feature, all you have to do is follow the usual process to upload a photo, but before you hit <em>Publish</em> make sure you've moved the Share to Facebook slider to the ON position. Now when you publish your photo to 23snaps, it will simultaneously <strong>post to Facebook</strong>.

There are a couple of things you need to remember here, first; you will need to link your 23snaps account to your Facebook account (if you have not already done so). When you complete the process above you will be prompted to make this connection. Secondly, by moving Share to Facebook slider to On you are only enabling this setting for this one post, the default setting is Off, so if you wish to post every photo to both 23snaps and Facebook, you will need to select this option every time.]]></content:encoded>
