	<item>
				<title>What Do Your Connections See When You Invite Them to 23snaps?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/what-do-your-connections-see-when-you-invite-them-to-23snaps/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 22 Aug 2013 12:51:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095383</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: left;">When it comes to inviting family and friends to new websites and online services, it helps to know exactly what they see and need to do to join you. You also want to be sure that your contacts' email addresses are protected, and you're not going to inadvertently sign them up to receive spam emails or confusing messages. There's nothing more frustrating than wanting to share a newly discovered site but not knowing for sure how invitations work, so we wanted to share exactly what happens when you invite someone to connect with you on 23snaps.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Sending the Invite</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">After you invite someone to connect with you, either through the 23snaps app or by <a href="http://www.23snaps.com/account/friendsfamily/#frmInviteFamilyFriends">inviting someone online</a>, they receive  a simple, clear email invitation that looks like this:</p>


[caption id="attachment_397400" align="aligncenter" width="640"]<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/invite-example.png"><img class="wp-image-39740095385 " alt="invite-example" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/invite-example.png" width="640" height="718" /></a> Example of an invitation that is sent by email when you invite family or friends to connect on 23snaps.[/caption]
<p style="text-align: left;">There are a couple things we wanted to make very clear in the email invitation:</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>How to accept it.</em> With both a text link and a big button, it should be very easy for your family and friends to move to the next step in the acceptance process.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>Who it's from.</em> We repeat the name of the sender (you) and your children a couple of times, just to make it very clear that this is a personalized invite from someone they actually know.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>That it's a real, trustworthy service.</em> By including some photographs you've already added to 23snaps, we can help your contacts understand that you trust 23snaps, and they can too.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>What 23snaps does.</em> A small message at the end of the email helps your contacts understand what 23snaps is, and the photos in the email give them a small taste of the special memories they will get to share.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">No response? No problem - we send <strong>one</strong> email reminder just in case the first one got lost or missed among other email messages. But we hate spam and don't want to send too many messages, so we only send one reminder. Think a family member missed your invite? You can always give them a call or send them a personalized email to follow up.</p>
<a name="subscribe"></a> 
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Accepting the Invite</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Once your family member or friend has clicked the 'Accept Invitation' link, they are taken to a confirmation page that explains that they will now begin receiving email digests with your latest content. If they wish, they can enter their details to create a full 23snaps account which will allow them to add comments and smiles, upload photos of their own, and manage their email settings.</p>

<p style="text-align: left;">Many relatives just want to receive 23snaps updates - and all of your beautiful photos - by email and don't want to worry about managing an online profile or account with a new website. That's ok! Once they click the "Accept Invitation" link and see the page in the screenshot below, they will receive emails only when you add new photos, videos or updates.</p>


[caption id="attachment_397400" align="aligncenter" width="669"]<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/invite-accepted.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740095389" alt="invite-accepted" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/invite-accepted.png" width="669" height="447" /></a> An example of the page that your connections see when they click the "Accept Invitation" link in the 23snaps invite email.[/caption]
<p style="text-align: left;">Here are the things we wanted to make clear with the 'invite accepted' page:</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <i>You don't need to do anything else</i>. If someone isn't particularly comfortable with technology, this page makes it clear they don't <em>have</em> to do anything - they have successfully accepted your invitation.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>New photos will arrive by email</em>. Your contact should expect future emails that contain more pictures, videos and updates.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">- <em>There's more to 23snaps, so they should create an account</em>. If your contacts want to see all of your previously uploaded photos, to leave comments or access additional 23snaps features, they should create an account with 23snaps themselves.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Receiving Email Digests</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Once your family member or friend has accepted your invite, whether they are just receiving email updates or they have created a full account, they will begin receiving email updates with any new photos, videos and updates you add. They will only receive at most one email per day - and only if you have added new content to 23snaps. The email update is really just a showcase for your newest updates - an easy way for your connections to enjoy those special memories. They can click on a picture to see a larger version and leave comments.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">If you or your contacts prefer to receive emails less (or more!) frequently, it's easy to <a href="http://www.23snaps.com/account/settings">change your email settings online</a>.</p>


[caption id="attachment_397400" align="aligncenter" width="672"]<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/digestexamples.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-39740095384 " alt="digestexamples" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/digestexamples.png" width="672" height="507" /></a> Example of the email digests your connections receive when you add new photos, videos or updates to 23snaps.[/caption]

&nbsp;

A couple of notes about email digests:

- <em>It's easy to unsubscribe</em>. Every email has an unsubscribe link. This link doesn't get used very often (turns out people really, really like receiving email updates with photos of the children they love) but if for any reason they need it, it's clear how to get the emails to stop.

- <i>It's all about the photos</i>. There's no unnecessary text and no advertising. Just your photos, videos and updates front and center.

<strong>23snaps Makes It Easy to Connect to Anyone in Your Family</strong>

23snaps was built with families in mind. And we know that some members of your family may be more, or less, comfortable with technology than others. Regardless, you may want to know exactly what your friends and family see when you invite them to join you on 23snaps. 23snaps invitations are clear, easy to accept and are a spam-free first step to sharing your precious memories with the people you love.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Will your children respect your privacy online?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/will-your-children-respect-your-privacy-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 28 Aug 2013 12:44:11 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095400</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Teenager-hiding-from-the-camera.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095406" alt="23snaps; Will your children respect your privacy online? 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Teenager-hiding-from-the-camera.jpg" width="640" height="358" /></a>

Hopefully, as your children grow up and start engaging on social media, they will have learnt from your example that <strong>protecting their privacy online in paramount</strong>. With any luck they will know how to keep their personal information private and that they need to carefully consider the consequences before they post anything about themselves online.

We all know that a teenager would never willingly embarrass themselves in front of their friends, so you can be sure they will carefully eliminate any potentially embarrassing or unflattering images of themselves before even considering uploading them. However ... <strong>how can you be sure that they will extend the same courtesy to you?</strong>

With every advancing year, we tend to get more selective about the photos we post of ourselves on the internet, and as adults we might like to argue that we should have the full rights over what is posted about us online. However, if you have not considered this attitude from your child's perspective, it will be much harder to impress upon them that they need to consider how comfortable you would be about the potential content before posting about you online. It is important to <strong>establish these boundaries early on</strong> and, as the parent, to respect both sides. If you post photos of your children online, especially children that are old enough to be aware of the online presence you are creating for them, you should definitely be asking them how they feel about it before you use their image.

As your kids get a little bit older there are a few things you could try to help them develop an understanding of what you would consider acceptable photo sharing etiquette.

<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-39740095404" alt="23snaps; Will your children respect your privacy online? 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Family-with-a-tablet.jpeg" width="206" height="206" />

When posting content that involves them, <strong>give them some options</strong> to choose from so that they can feel involved in the sharing process.

<strong>Come to an agreement</strong> that will prevent any member of the family posting photos of each other without their permission.

<strong>Ask them</strong> whether they are comfortable with you posting pictures of them on mutual social networks.

<strong>Use good judgement</strong>. If you know they will hate the photo, keep it for your own enjoyment, don't share it with the world.

We'd also love to hear some of your suggestions about how you manage this situation. How does your family help to protect each others privacy?

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Content ordered chronologically</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-content-ordered-chronologically/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Sep 2013 11:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740094169</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr">We never want you to miss out on enjoying the content your friends and family share on 23snaps, which is why we make sure that the newest, most recently uploaded photos, videos and updates get prime position at the top of your Newsfeed. The entire Newsfeed is arranged in order of upload date, so the longer a photo has been on 23snaps, the further down the list it will go … to make sure there is always room at the top for the exciting new content that is shared with you everyday.</p>
<p dir="ltr">However, as 23snaps was designed as an online journal, so we also want to enable our users to view content in chronological order. This arrangement can be found in each child’s individual profile. Here you will see any photo, video or update that the child is tagged in; arranged in order of the date that the content was created, as opposed to the date it was uploaded.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><em>                                             Newsfeed                                                                                      Timeline</em></p>
<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Content-Order.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-39740095454 alignnone" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Content-Order.jpg" alt="23snaps-Content-Order" width="1078" height="990" /></a></p>
<p dir="ltr">The order of the content uploaded to 23snaps will always follow this pattern, whether you are using the <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=blog&amp;c=TOTW">iPhone or iPad app</a>, the <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/com.snaps23.android?pid=blog&amp;c=TOTW">Android app</a> or on the <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_content_order">23snaps website</a>.</p>
&nbsp;

				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Editing Existing Posts</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-editing-existing-posts/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 30 Aug 2013 11:30:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095414</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Imagine taking the time to lovingly build a beautiful digital journal for your child but, when you want to look back and enjoy your previous posts, there it is, blighting your perfect timeline ... A TYPO!! Oh horror of horrors, what are you going to do?!

This is a feeling no <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_editing">23snaps</a> user will ever have to experience, because we allow you to go back and edit past posts simply and easily via our <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_editing">website</a>. This feature allows you to retroactively change the date, description and tags that you have added to your photos, videos and updates. Any changes will take effect immediately.

All you have to do is log into your account on the 23snaps <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_editing">website</a> locate the post you wish to edit. Then, click on the gear icon located beneath the bottom right corner of your post.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/wnpdlwtnbcp1hr8/?name=1.jpg" alt="1.jpg" width="450" />

Select the <em>Edit </em>option from the dropdown menu

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/ggpti3qzge2owvq/?name=2.jpg" alt="2.jpg" width="450" />

Now you can make any changes you want, just make sure you remember to click <em>Save</em> when you’re done to ensure the edits are made.

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/3dwilvbqjns3zqq/?name=3.jpg" alt="3.jpg" width="450" />

We're certain that you will have absolutely no difficulties using our simple editing feature, but if you do have any questions or would like any assistance, feel free to get in touch at <a href="mailto:support@23snaps.com">support(at)23snaps(dot)com</a>, or leave a comment below!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Should you create a social profile for your child before they are technically old enough?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/should-you-create-a-social-profile-for-your-child-before-they-are-technically-old-enough/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 30 Aug 2013 13:23:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095419</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/child-at-a-computer.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740095424" alt="child at a computer" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/child-at-a-computer.jpg" width="648" height="339" /></a>

Most social networks impose an <strong>age restriction of 13 years old</strong>, this is due to COPPA, the Child Online Privacy Protection Act, which prevents companies from collecting information of a personal nature from a child. However, there are numerous accounts registered to Facebook, Instagram, Pinterest and Snapchat that belong to children aged 12 years and under, as there is an easy way  for kids to get around this restriction ... <strong>lie about their age</strong>.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Facebook-logo-ICON-02.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095432" alt="23snaps; Facebook logo" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Facebook-logo-ICON-02-150x150.png" width="135" height="135" /></a>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Instagram-logo.jpeg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095433" style="margin-left: 5px;" alt="23snaps; Instagram logo" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Instagram-logo-150x150.jpeg" width="135" height="135" /></a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Pinterest-Logo-Vector-by-Jon-Bennallick-02.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095434" style="margin-left: 5px;" alt="23snaps; Pinterest logo" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Pinterest-Logo-Vector-by-Jon-Bennallick-02-150x150.png" width="135" height="135" /></a><img class=" wp-image-39740095435 alignleft" style="margin-left: 10px;" alt="23snaps; Snapchat logo" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/tech-snapchat-logo-150x150.jpg" width="135" height="135" />

&nbsp;

There are so many parents that consider helping their children skirt these age restrictions in order to allow them to interact online, but <strong>is it really a good idea?</strong> We wanted to discuss the pros and cons of letting your child use social networks before they are officially of age.

<strong>Benefits:</strong>

If you allow your child to register an account with a social network at a young age, you could use it as a bargaining tool to allow you to create, and enforce, stricter rules regarding their usage and how you would monitor that usage. This could help you to <strong>teach them about responsible conduct</strong> and how they are expected to behave online, as you would likely be much more involved in their (access/interaction?posting).

It is obvious that social media isn't going to go away any time soon, and much like with learning any other skill, introducing them to it an earlier age may <strong>help them to develop their (skill)</strong> and become more comfortable with using social media as a life tool.

If all of your child's social circle have been allowed to create social profiles for themselves and your child has not, the unfortunate truth is that there is a good chance they will end up getting left out. If plans are made on a platform that your child does not have access too, they could find themselves being left behind by their friends. Allowing them to join in with their peers online will mean they <strong>feel more involved</strong>.

<strong>Detriments:</strong>

Children under the age of 13 are really <strong>not emotionally mature enough</strong> to handle a situation that might arise involving cyber bullying. Whether they are being targeted, or being encouraged to join in when the target is someone else, it is unlikely that a child of such a young age will be able to deal with the possible harm it could do to their psyche.

There is a lot of content online that many of us would consider inappropriate for anyone to see, but graphic violent, or sexual, images  are out there, and children of such a young age should most definitely be prevented from accidentally stumbling across <strong>unsuitable images and videos</strong>.

It is difficult for a child of that age to understand the concept of permanence, posting something now means that it could potentially be online forever, and they will more than likely <strong>regret any photos or information that they shar</strong>e about themselves now, 10 years down the line.

We by no means feel that we are in a position where we can make this decision for you, however our recommendation would be that you avoid allowing your child free access to a social media site before they meet the minimum age requirement. The Child Online Privacy Protection act was put in place to <strong>protect children</strong>, not to ruin their fun, and it's a good idea to adhere by those rules. Waiting a year or two really isn't going to mean that much to your kids in the long run.

However if your child really isn't willing to wait, and they're desperate to have a way to build a profile online now, why not set them up with their own <strong><a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=child_soc_net">23snaps</a></strong> account? They can learn how to <strong>use a social network in a private environment</strong> and share photos with the family whilst you're able to keep an eye on them.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>A professional photographer&#039;s guide to taking the best photos of your children.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/taking-the-best-photos-of-children-a-professional-photographers-perspective/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 04 Sep 2013 09:25:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095466</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-Moore.jpg"><img class="wp-image-39740095488 alignright" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;" alt="Sophie Moore" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-Moore-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a>Sophie is a professional photographer, based in the West Sussex area (UK), whose speciality is photographing newborns and children. She is a mum of 1 (with another one on the way!), so she has real insight into what it takes to capture the perfect photo because she really understands what is needed both from a parental, and photographic, perspective. She is a registered member of the Official Guild of Photographers and also an approved member of the Butterfly Wishes Network, where she photographs children and families with life threatening and terminal illnesses.

Photography is not only Sophie's job, it's her passion. She chose to specialise in natural family and children's photography simply because she loves to be able to give the families she works with something that will be treasured. That's why she wants to help you capture all of those precious moments that pass by so quickly!

Here are Sophie's top tips for taking the best possible photos of your kids, along with some example's of her work.

&nbsp;

<strong>Wait until they're immersed in their own little world</strong>, they don’t always have to be looking at the camera! Wait until they’re playing or distracted by something other than the photography session. Whether they're fascinated by a bug, involved in a puzzle or just staring out the window, don’t disturb them and catch them unaware. You’ll get some brilliant expressions and a little glimpse into a world all their own.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-1.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740095468 alignnone" alt="23snaps: Little Miss Photography" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-1.png" width="315" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-2.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095469" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-2.png" width="315" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Don’t be afraid to get in close</strong>. One of the things we are most enamoured by are their tiny, delicate features, these are what we marvel over and don’t want to forget. They change so quickly, so preserve the memory of tiny hands and wide eyes by getting in nice and close. Whether it’s zooming, cropping or moving in, get right up close and personal. They’ve not yet developed that fear of cameras a lot of us adults have, so make the most of it!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-3.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095470" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 3" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-3.png" width="275" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-4.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095471" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 4" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-4.png" width="352" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Capture them in action</strong>. We all know how hard it is to get a child to pause for photos, so don’t ask them to. Kids are active and fun, and you want to catch that. The key to great action shots is using different angles and being able to zoom.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-5.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095472" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 5" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-5.png" width="315" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-6.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095473" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 6" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-6.png" width="315" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Change the angles and play with the composition</strong>. Challenge yourself to use different angles, the more the merrier, and you’ll soon find your favourites and the ones that work best for you. Make sure you take the time to think about the photo and exactly what you want to capture in it. Remove anything from your environment that you don’t want to end up in the photo, either by changing your angle or picking the thing up and moving it (where possible). It's also a good idea to try and avoid capturing any features that might draw attention away from the child in the finished image. And remember ... sometimes simplicity is key.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-8.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095474" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 8" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-8.png" width="315" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-9.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095475" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 9" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-9.png" width="315" /></a>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-10.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095476" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 10" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-10.png" width="315" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-11.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095477" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 11" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-11.png" width="315" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Make them laugh</strong>. Do whatever it takes. Dance, pull funny faces, or tell them their favourite jokes. Who cares about looking silly? Certainly not them! Just have some fun with it.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-12.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095478" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 12" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-12.png" width="315" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-13.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095479" alt="23snaps: Little MIss Photography 13" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Sophie-13.png" width="315" /></a>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em style="text-align: center;"> Photos by Sophie Moore of Little Miss Photography</em></p>
If you're interested in arranging a photography session with Sophie, you can find all of her contact information on her <a href="http://littlemissphotos.co.uk/contact/">website</a>. She's a wonder with kids and comes with the 23snaps seal of approval!"]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Give 23snaps as a gift.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/give-23snaps-as-a-gift/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Sep 2013 10:52:22 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095501</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Stuck for an idea for a cute <strong>gift for a loved one</strong>? Why not give the gift of 23snaps? Whether you're looking for a gift for Christmas, Birthday, Mother's Day, Father's Day, Grandparent's Day, or any other day for that matter, <strong>23snaps can be a wonderful, personalised gift</strong> that can be enjoyed year round.

Want to know how to go about preparing 23snaps to present as a gift? All you'd need to do is <strong>register for a free 23snaps account</strong> either on our <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=gift">website</a> or by downloading the <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=blog&amp;c=gift">iOS</a>, <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/com.snaps23.android?pid=blog&amp;c=gift">Android</a>, or <a href="http://apps.microsoft.com/windows/en-gb/app/23snaps/8d8b50ab-fc02-49c5-a648-06b8fd586f9f">Windows 8</a> app. Then you can <strong>start building a beautiful digital journal</strong> using photos, videos and updates about your family.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Give-the-Gift-of-23snaps.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-39740095502" alt="Give the Gift of 23snaps" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Give-the-Gift-of-23snaps-1024x575.jpg" width="640" height="359" /></a>

Once you're happy with how your journal looks, you can invite the recipient of this fabulous gift to <strong>share the journal</strong> with you. Simply send them an email invite from within your 23snaps account (or, if you want to go old school, you could write instructions as to where to find their gift in their birthday/christmas/mother's day card, kind of like a treasure map!). They too would then need to register for a free account to gain unlimited access to the content included in the digital timeline. They could even share the task of building the journal with you. How lovely it would be to receive <strong>a family journal that continues to grow</strong>, even after the day it is presented.

As an added bonus, you can send them a <strong>physical copy of the journal</strong> in the form of a 23snaps photobook. Our photobooks start from only $23, and that covers the cost of shipping to anywhere in the world!

23snaps would make a fantastic gift, filled with precious moments that the receiver can enjoy again and again. And the best part? <strong>It's completely free!</strong>

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>New Feature! Multiple photo uploads.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/new-feature-multiple-photo-uploads/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 17 Sep 2013 11:30:27 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095514</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We have an <strong>exciting new feature</strong> to announce! You can now upload <strong>multiple photos in one go</strong> via the <a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=blog&amp;c=multiple_uploads">iPhone and iPad app</a>! (Don't worry Android users, this feature is not far away for you either!) This feature is also available on the <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=multiple_uploads">23snaps website</a>.

Not only that, but now if you use the multiple upload feature, you don't need to worry about flooding your connections' Newsfeeds with post after post, because <strong>they will all be batched together</strong> in a cute little mosaic view for anyone that wants to view them via the app.

To help you get started, we've supplied an easy to follow step-by-step guide, complete with screenshots to show you how beautifully displayed your photos will be.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-1.png"><img class="wp-image-39740095515 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px" alt="23snaps; Multiple Uploads 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-1.png" width="176" height="264" /></a>

- To use this fab new feature on the mobile app, all you have to do is click on the menu button in the top right corner of the screen and <strong>select </strong><em><strong>Photos</strong> </em>(NB. if you click on the <em>Photo</em> button you will still only be able to upload 1 image, so make sure you pick the plural).

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="wp-image-39740095517 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px" alt="23snaps; Multiple Uploads 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-3.png" width="176" height="263" />- Now you need to select all of the images you want to upload, there is a <strong>maximum of 15 images per batch</strong>. Once you have made your selection, click <em>Done</em>.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="wp-image-39740095518 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px" alt="23snaps; Multiple Uploads 3" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-4.png" width="176" height="263" />- You can now <strong>add individual tags and descriptions to each image</strong>. To add a tag simply tap the avatar of the child in the image (if you have only one child, they will be tagged automatically, but you can remove the tag by tapping on their image). To add a description, simply tap the screen where it says <em>Tap to add description ...</em><em>
</em>

Once you've added all of the details, click <em>Upload</em>.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="wp-image-39740095519 alignleft" style="margin-right: 10px" alt="23snaps; Multiple Uploads 4" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-5.png" width="176" height="263" />- <strong>The images will be posted to your Newsfeed in a batch</strong>. However if you go into your child's timeline, they will be displayed normally.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_1.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/vpnsi1ypw3kfqxg/?name=Batch+upload+1.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

To <strong>upload multiple photos on the website</strong> all you have to do is click on the orange <em><strong>+</strong> Post</em> button in the top right corner of the screen.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_2.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/vrdj3ebqrur6xfv/?name=Batch+upload+2.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

Select the <em>Photo</em> option. There is only one option here, so <strong>you don't need to remember to select either the singular or plural</strong>.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<br class="Apple-interchange-newline" /><img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_3.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/xpcgoab2v8uzkhf/?name=Batch+upload+3.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

Then<strong> click </strong><em><strong>Select Files</strong>. </em>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_4.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/ojamninilgxautm/?name=Batch+upload+4.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

From the list on the left of the lightbox, <strong>select the location from which you would like to upload your images</strong> and click <em>Choose File. </em>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_5.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/zftpa2tlosit4rd/?name=Batch+upload+5.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

<strong>Select all</strong> of the photos you wish to upload and click <em>Open. </em>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<img class="alignright" style="margin-left: 10px" alt="Batch_upload_6.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/cht401kioixiz23/?name=Batch+upload+6.jpg" width="270" height="169" />

Now you will have the option to <strong>individually alter the dates, tags and descriptions for each photo</strong>. When you are ready to upload, click <em>Submit Photos </em>at the bottom of the screen.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

We hope you enjoy using the new feature! We know a lot of our users have been waiting for this with great anticipation, and we're so glad to be able to provide it for you.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Start a Scrapbook Collection</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-start-a-scrapbook-collection/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 13 Sep 2013 11:30:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095551</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Make the most of your 23snaps digital journal, and <strong>turn it into a scrapbook</strong> for your child too! You’re probably already using the app to post photos of your child, but what about everything else that helps <strong>build the story of their life</strong>, don’t you want to document that too? The newspaper headline on the day they were born, the hospital bracelet your baby was wearing when you brought them home, the first pair of shoes that they grew out of and the painting that your little one did for you at nursery. Why not take photos of all of these things as a <strong>super simple way of treasuring them</strong>. Instead of putting these things into a box where you will most likely never look at them, simply snap a photo and upload it to your child’s timeline, then you can go back and enjoy all of the little things again and again. You can even <strong>start a “Scrapbook” collection</strong>, and add all of these snaps to one album so they’re even easier to look back on and enjoy.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/TOTW-scrapbook-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095552" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/TOTW-scrapbook-2-651x1024.jpg" alt="TOTW scrapbook 2" width="172" height="270" /></a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/TOTW-Scrapbook.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095553" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/TOTW-Scrapbook-1024x575.jpg" alt="TOTW Scrapbook" width="435" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Set 23snaps Reminders</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-set-23snaps-reminders/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 20 Sep 2013 11:30:02 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095564</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We all know that being a parent means you're super busy, all the time! When you are sleep deprived, and have a tiny human's life in your hands, it's easy to forgot to post photos, videos and updates to 23snaps. But make sure you don't miss out on building a fantastically comprehensive timeline for your child, as well as keeping the family up to date, by setting a regular reminder on your device to remind you to upload new content.

Most of our users use one of our 23snaps mobile apps to keep their 23snaps accounts updated, and if you're anything like the rest of the world; we're pretty sure that your smartphone/tablet is becoming an extension of your arm. That means that you will almost always have it with you, and a discreet reminder will prompt you to pull out that device and snap a photo. Set the reminder for anytime of day that is convenient for you, and to repeat daily, weekly or however frequently you choose, and post away!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screenshot_2013-09-03-17-20-53.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095565" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screenshot_2013-09-03-17-20-53-576x1024.png" alt="Set a 23snaps reminder 1" width="315" height="560" /></a>   <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screenshot_2013-09-03-17-21-30.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095566" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screenshot_2013-09-03-17-21-30-576x1024.png" alt="Set a 23snaps reminder 2" width="315" /></a>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>39740095564</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date>2013-09-20 11:30:02</wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt>2013-09-20 11:30:02</wp:post_date_gmt>

	<item>
				<title>See how much your child changes with a photo a day</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/see-how-your-child-changes-with-a-photo-a-day/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 Sep 2013 11:30:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095583</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Aiden-1-6-months.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740095587" alt="23snaps; A Photo a Day" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Aiden-1-6-months.jpg" width="640" /></a>

Every child is different, they learn and change and grow at completely different rates, but one thing is for certain ... they will grow faster than you ever could have imagined! Make sure that you and your loved ones never have to miss a moment; by simply snapping one quick photo a day you can build a beautiful log of just how quickly your little bundle of joy changes. How you choose to take your photos is entirely up to you! You could try and catch them in the same position every day, maybe once you've put them down to bed, to have an easy comparison, or you can use this as an excuse to get out and do fun things with your child to help make some amazing memories. However you choose to undertake the challenge, you will be astounded at the difference in your child from day to day, and week to week, but you will also have a amazingly extensive log that you can look back and treasure on when they are all grown up.

For some great tips on how to take the best possible photos of your children, check out some tips from one of our favorite child photographers, <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/taking-the-best-photos-of-children-a-professional-photographers-perspective/">Sophie Moore</a>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps on the BBC</title>

	<item>
				<title>Limit your children&#039;s screen-time</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/limit-your-childrens-screen-time/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 24 Sep 2013 11:08:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095610</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Limit-you-childrens-screen-time-11.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740095616" alt="23snaps; Limit you children's screen-time 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Limit-you-childrens-screen-time-11.jpg" width="639" height="293" /></a></p>
<p dir="ltr">Now that the kids are back in school it is so important to <strong>establish some limitations on their screen time</strong>, whether that’s sitting in front of the computer, playing on their smartphone or even staring at the TV. Allowing your child free rein over the amount of tech time they get to participate in could result in a lack of sleep and lower grades. <a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/children-and-tv/MY00522">Past research</a> has shown a direct <strong>correlation between excessive screen time and irregular sleep, behavioural problems, impaired academic performance and even obesity</strong>.</p>
<p dir="ltr">A study published in <a href="http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/early/2010/06/14/peds.2009-3374.abstract">Pediatrics</a>, the official journal of the American Academy of Pediatrics, found that parents who establish clearly defined rules for the maximum consumption of tech they allow, are <strong>more likely to have those rules obeyed</strong> than the parents of children who consider their parents’ opinion on screen time a recommendation rather than a rule.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The key is to approach the issue in the same way you do any other rule, such as wearing seat belts or cleaning teeth; <strong>as an expectation, not a request</strong>.  While you should discuss the reason for screen-time limits and appropriate media content with your children, these rules should not be up for negotiation.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Limit-your-childrens-screen-time-2.jpg"><img class="alignright  wp-image-39740095614" style="margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;" alt="23snaps; Limit your children's screen-time 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/23snaps-Limit-your-childrens-screen-time-2.jpg" width="325" height="251" /></a>A brilliant way of implementing a set of strict guidelines, whilst still allowing your child some flexibility, is to <strong>set up a weekly, rather than daily, time allowance</strong> or “screen-time budget”. This way your children will also learn a bit about time management. If you had originally planned to allow your children half an hour of screen-time each week day, with an hour on both Saturday and Sunday, why not try allowing them a 4 and a half hour limit weekly? They are then allowed to choose when to use their time, if they choose to squander their entire budget on one day, they will regret it later in the week, and possibly <strong>learn to manage their time better</strong> in the future.</p>
<p dir="ltr">There are a couple of things you’ll need to take into consideration before you start. If you have no idea of how much time your kids are currently spending glued to the screen, it could be difficult to determine what an acceptable limit would be.  If you’re unsure of this, spend a week observing and tally up exactly how much time each family member spends on tech, this will then <strong>help to determine how much time you think is acceptable</strong>.</p>
<p dir="ltr">You will also need to decide what your kids will need to use their allotted time for, and what is exempt. <strong>Will doing their homework or emailing Grandma have to be worked into their own budgeted time?</strong> If so, you will need to be more generous with how much time they’re allowed. If not, you need to find an appropriate way to monitor when they are doing the “fun stuff” without being constantly tethered to their side.</p>
An open discussion about <strong>why you’re implementing these rules, the benefits that they can have, and the consequences that will occur if they are broken</strong>, should allow your whole family to come up with a system that everyone understands, and is willing to stick to.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Preventing Your Children From Buying Apps and Making In-App Purchases</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/preventing-your-children-from-buying-apps-and-making-in-app-purchases/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 26 Sep 2013 09:04:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095624</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screen-Shot-2013-09-25-at-16.50.53.png"><img class="wp-image-39740095652 alignnone" alt="23Snaps; preventing in-app purchases" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screen-Shot-2013-09-25-at-16.50.53.png" width="640" height="287" /></a>

<strong>Preventing your child from inadvertently buying apps and making in-app purchases</strong> should definitely be a priority. We've all heard the stories about unfortunate parents receiving their monthly phone bill, only to discover that their little rascal has inadvertently <a href="http://www.moneysavingexpert.com/news/phones/2013/02/kids-spent-3200-iphone-avoid-app-charge-hell">racked up massive costs from downloading apps</a>, or buying add-ons for the games that they love to play. Usually, gaining access to a parents iPhone, iPad or Android device requires the little one to memorise only 1 password which, considering how tech-savvy kids are becoming, is by no means an impossible task. When that same password is used to access the App-Store, terrible things can happen!!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screen-Shot-2013-09-25-at-16.58.39.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095657" style="margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 5px;" alt="23snaps; preventing in-app purchases" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screen-Shot-2013-09-25-at-16.58.39-300x191.png" width="251" height="160" /></a>We would always advise that if your children regularly use your device, that you <strong>use a series of different passwords</strong> to ensure that your bank balance is protected. It really is not advisable to let your child know the password you have set for the App Store on your device, if they wish to purchase anything, or even download a free app, ensuring they have to <strong>come and ask you for your permission</strong> allows you to not only safeguard your bank balance, but also monitor what apps they are using and whether they are appropriate.

Apple's new Touch ID security system, that requires the iPhone 5s user to <strong>scan their finger print to unlock their device</strong>, could provide an extra barrier between your child and the App-Store, as you can set the Touch ID up in place of your Apple Store password. You do have the option of saving up to 5 different finger prints that are able to unlock the device, which would allow you to give your entire family access to your phone. However you are only able to set 1 fingerprint in place of your App-Store Password, which <strong>would prevent anyone other than you from making any kind of purchase</strong> ... unless of course your child in some kind of <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24203929">super hacker</a>!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-21.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-39740095648" alt="23snaps; prevent in app purchases" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-21-200x300.png" width="200" height="300" /></a>There is also the option to <strong>disable in-app purchases completely</strong> on any iOS device, but if you also enjoy playing games on your phone, this may hinder you. Nevertheless we thought we should provide you with some easy to follow instructions on how it's done!

- Open 'Settings' then choose 'General', and then 'Restrictions'.

- Tap 'Enable Restrictions', choose a PIN and enter it a second time to confirm.

- Now you can set any restrictions from the menu. In the 'Allowed Content' menu, slide 'In app purchases' to 'Off'.

With an Android device, you don't have this option, but you can ensure that <strong>your password is asked for EVERY TIME</strong> a purchase is attempted.

If you don't want to disable in app purchases, and you don't have access to Touch ID, <strong>regularly changing your App Store password</strong> and explaining to your children that <strong>they should not agree to download anything on to your device without your express permission</strong>, should prevent any "accidental" purchases and a whopping great phone bill at the end of the month!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip Of The Week: Multiple Photo Uploads</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-top-of-the-week-multiple-photo-uploads/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 27 Sep 2013 11:30:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095668</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[This weeks tip announces our newest feature! We have had so many requests for <strong>multiple photo uploads</strong>, and so our tech team have been busy working away and now ... TA DA! It's all ready for you to enjoy*.

You can now post numerous photos with just a few clicks on the 23snaps app! The <strong>photos will then be batched together</strong> so as not to flood your connections’ timelines and risk them missing out on any of your beautiful new snaps.

All you have to do is <strong>click on the plus (+) button</strong> in the top right corner of the screen and select <em><strong>Photos</strong> </em>(NB. if you click on the <em>Photo</em> button you will still only be able to upload 1 image, so make sure you pick the plural).

<img src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/um2th38cg1zp6or/?name=photo+1.PNG" alt="photo_1.PNG" width="200" />

Next you need to select all of the images you want to upload, there is a <strong>maximum of 15 images</strong> per batch. Once you have made your selection, click <strong><em>Done</em></strong>.

<img title="New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-3.png" alt="photo 3 New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." width="200" />

You can now <strong>add individual tags and descriptions</strong> to each image. To add a tag simply tap the avatar of the child in the image (if you have only one child, they will be tagged automatically, but you can remove the tag by tapping on their avatar). To add a description, simply tap the screen where it says <em>Tap to add description …</em>

Once you’ve added all of the details, click <strong><em>Upload</em></strong>.

<img title="New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-4.png" alt="photo 4 New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." width="200" />

The images will be posted to your Newsfeed in a batch. However if you go into your child’s timeline, they will be displayed normally.

<img title="New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/photo-5.png" alt="photo 5 New Feature! Multiple photo uploads." width="200" />

*<em>This feature is not yet available for Android users, but we hope to release within the next week or 2!</em>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>5 Photos Of Your Children That You Shouldn&#039;t Share Online</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/5-photos-of-your-children-that-you-shouldnt-share-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 01 Oct 2013 13:33:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095677</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[The debate over <strong>whether parents should or should not post photos of their kids online</strong> is still going strong, every parent has their own opinion and that's fine. Some people are so uncomfortable with the thought of sharing their child's image online that they refrain completely, whilst others seem to post their child's every waking moment on wide open social network sites. It is down to each family to decide what is right for them, but if you do choose to upload you kid's photos to a social networking site, we feel that there are a <strong>few types of photo that you should avoid sharing</strong>; unless you are absolutely sure that your privacy settings are rock solid, and you're confident the people you are connected to won't share your photos to a wider audience.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Bathtime.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-39740095678 alignnone" alt="23snaps; Bathtime" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Bathtime-300x201.jpg" width="300" height="201" /></a>

<em><strong>Bath-time</strong></em>

Unless you have very unusual bathing habits, your little one is going to be naked during their bath. There is no denying that a grinning baby surrounded by bubbles is one of the most adorable photos around, but naked photos on the internet? That just screams no-no to us!

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/School-Uniform.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095682" alt="23snaps; School Uniform" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/School-Uniform-225x300.jpg" width="225" height="300" /></a>

<em><strong>School Uniform </strong></em>

Every responsible social media user knows never to post personal details in a public space, such as your full name, address, telephone number etc. By posting a photo of your child in their school uniform, you are advertising to a world full of strangers where your child will be 7 hours a day, 5 days a week.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Playdate.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095680" alt="Playdate" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Playdate-300x201.jpg" width="300" height="201" /></a>

<em><strong>Play-dates with multiple children that are not your own</strong></em>

Photo posting etiquette dictates that you never share photos of other people children online without express permission from the child's parents. How would you feel if someone else did it to you? Keep those photos offline, you can always email them to the parent's of the other children if they'd like to see them,

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Embarrassing.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095679" alt="Embarrassing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Embarrassing-184x300.jpg" width="184" height="300" /></a>

<em><strong>Embarrassing photos </strong></em>

Looking back over old baby photos is a favourite pass-time for many kids (and adults!), and there are always those few that will make you cringe, but imagine if that was available for the whole world to see. Photos are designed to capture a memory, not provide fodder that will knock your child down. Keep those amusing photos to yourself, and laugh over them as a family, away from prying eyes.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/poor-behaviour.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740095681" alt="Naughty child stands in the corner" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/poor-behaviour-200x300.jpg" width="200" height="300" /></a>

<em><strong>Bad Behaviour</strong></em>

Highlighting poor behaviour by sharing it online will only encourage your child (especially a slightly older child) to repeat it. They'll think what they're doing is a good thing because you're choosing to share it with other people. It could also be potentially embarrassing for you as a parent, public tantrums can be unavoidable, so why would you want to take a private altercation and put it out there for others to gawk at?

If you do want to post every photo of your child online for your friends and family to see, we would recommend using <strong><a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=5_photos_not_to_share">23snaps</a></strong>. At least then you can rest assured that your photos are confined to an entirely private space, unlike many other social networks who have slightly more ambiguous privacy settings.]]></content:encoded>

		</wp:postmeta>

	</item>
	<item>
				<title>Google+ Photo Editing Tool - Basic Adjustments</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/google-photo-editing-tool-basic-adjustments/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 03 Oct 2013 14:15:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095688</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We've just discovered an <strong>AMAZING new photo editing tool</strong>, and we felt we just had to share it with you! The Google+ photo editing system is incredible, and we recommend everyone starts using it. Right. Now.

The one very minor drawback to using this system is that it is <strong>only available in Google Chrome</strong>, but we think it's definitely worth downloading <a href="play.google.com/store/‎">Chrome (for free!)</a>, even if this is all you use it for.

The point of this post is not only to introduce you to Google+ photo editing, but also to <strong>walk you through all of the different tools</strong> that are provided. As there are SO MANY of them, it will take a few posts to cover everything, so please keep an eye out for parts <strong><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/google-photo-editing-tool-creative-adjustments/">2</a></strong> &amp; <strong><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/google-photo-editing-tool-picassa-23snaps/">3</a></strong>!

First of all you need to <strong>upload your photo</strong>(s) to Google+.
<ol>
	<li>Open the Google+ main menu.</li>
	<li>Click on <strong>Photos</strong>.</li>
	<li>Click on <strong>Upload photos</strong>.</li>
</ol>
After you've uploaded your photo, you can choose to share it by creating a post, but this is entirely optional. Now on to the fun part; editing your image.

Open the photo you wish to work on, and select <em><strong>Edit</strong></em> from the menu bar at the top of the lightbox. There are 4 different ways in which you can make basic adjustments to your photo, these are Tune, Selective Adjust, Details, and Crop &amp; Rotate.

<strong>Tune Image</strong>

You can use this tool to create depth and vibrancy by adjusting the brightness, contrast, saturation, shadows or warmth levels. You can also select from a range of different preset effects. After selecting a preset, use the available controls to fine-tune the result.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.07.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095689" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.07-200x300.png" width="90" height="135" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.20.png"><img class="wp-image-39740095690 alignleft" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.20-200x300.png" width="90" height="135" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.31.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740095691 alignleft" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.31-201x300.png" width="90" height="134" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.41.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740095692 alignleft" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.41-198x300.png" width="90" height="136" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.50.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740095693 alignleft" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.17.50-198x300.png" width="90" height="136" /></a>     <img class=" wp-image-39740095694 alignleft" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.18.04-200x300.png" width="90" />

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<strong>Selective adjust</strong>

If there is just one area of your photo you want to alter, you can do it with this tool. Just select the part of the photo you wish to tune using a control point. Each control point that you place automatically selects surrounding objects based on similar hue, saturation and brightness. For example, you might adjust the brightness of the sky without changing the beach in the foreground. You then have the option to adjust the brightness, contrast,  and saturation of your selected area.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.30.47.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095697" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps: Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.30.47-200x300.png" width="141" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.06.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095698" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.06-199x300.png" width="141" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.40.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095699" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.40-199x300.png" width="141" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.56.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095700" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.31.56-200x300.png" width="141" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<strong>Details</strong>

This tool allows you to enhance the details and improve the sharpness of your photo. You can make adjustments manually or choose from a range of preset adjustments. After selecting a preset, use the available controls to fine-tune the result.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.30.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095702" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps: Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.30-200x300.png" width="141" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.41.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095703" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps: Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.41-198x300.png" width="141" height="212" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.51.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095704" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps: Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.41.51-202x300.png" width="141" height="212" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.42.09.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095705" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps: Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.42.09-200x300.png" width="141" height="212" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<strong>Crop and rotate</strong>

The final basic adjustment tool allows you to resize or remove distracting parts of your photo with standard aspect ratios or a free crop. You can also rotate or straighten photos.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.46.49.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095706" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.46.49-199x300.png" width="90" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.06.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095707" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.06-141x300.png" width="85" height="180" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.24.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095708" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.24-151x300.png" width="85" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.53.png"><img style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.47.53-300x240.png" width="100" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.48.02.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095710" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.48.02-300x300.png" width="100" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.48.37.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095711" style="margin-right: 12px;" alt="23snaps; Google+ Photo Editing" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-10.48.37-169x300.png" width="100" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip Of The Week: Keeping Your Content in Chronological Order</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-keeping-your-content-in-chronological-order/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 04 Oct 2013 10:18:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740095723</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[When you upload a photo to 23snaps the images appear in the Newsfeed in order of upload date, this is to ensure that your connections are easily able to locate the newest content you have shared for them to enjoy. When you go to your child's timeline, the <strong>photos appear in chronological order</strong> so as to build an accurate journal for your child.

The photos dates in 23snaps are <strong>determined by the timestamp embedded in each image</strong>. In order to ensure that your photos are in the correct order, it is important to preserve the original image's metadata. If you have deleted, or altered, the metadata, it will prevent the app from recognising when the image was actually created.

<strong>How to avoid altering the timestamp:</strong>

If you are taking photos on a camera and then transferring them to your computer to upload to 23snaps, try dragging the images off of your device, rather than copying them, as this will preserve the metadata.

If you are taking a photo on a smart device or tablet remember that it is only the original image that contains the correct metadata, taking a screenshot of the image, or using photo editing software will create a new image with data that has a different creation date.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/5-Months-Old.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095725" style="margin-left: 25px; margin-right: 25px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/5-Months-Old.jpg" alt="23snaps; Image Timestamp" width="389" height="542" /></a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-11.32.59.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740095724" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Screen-Shot-2013-10-03-at-11.32.59.png" alt="23snaps: Image Timestamp" width="179" height="542" /></a>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>39740095723</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date>2013-10-04 10:18:59</wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt>2013-10-04 10:18:59</wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status>closed</wp:comment_status>
		<wp:ping_status>closed</wp:ping_status>
		<wp:post_name>23snaps-tip-of-the-week-keeping-your-content-in-chronological-order</wp:post_name>
		<wp:status>publish</wp:status>
		<wp:post_parent>0</wp:post_parent>
		<wp:menu_order>0</wp:menu_order>
		<wp:post_type>post</wp:post_type>
		<wp:post_password></wp:post_password>
		<wp:is_sticky>0</wp:is_sticky>
		<category domain="category" nicename="23snaps_tips_and_tricks"><![CDATA[23snaps Tips &amp; Tricks]]></category>
