	<item>
				<title>Is your child &#039;the bully&#039;?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/is-your-child-the-bully/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 19 Nov 2013 12:21:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096041</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Bullying is a topic that gets a lot of attention, however, in most cases, the attention is focused on the victim. But what should you do if you find out that your child is the bully? Many parents feel unequipped to deal with any situation in which their child is involved in bullying, it's difficult to accept that your little one whom you love so much could be causing another child to hurt. But it does happen, and we want to help by providing some really useful advice from some excellent resources.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.10.40.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-39740096044" alt="23snaps; Is your child the bully?" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.10.40.png" width="222" height="280" /></a>

<em><strong>What would you do if you found out your child was a bully?</strong></em>

"If I found out my child was a bully, first I would <em>not</em> be judgmental. Simply because all humans, children included, behave because they want their needs met. Bullying is often (not always!) a way to attract attention or to make new friends, in other words, it's sometimes a sign that social skills may need some attention, but there are of plenty other, much better and socially accepted, ways for accomplishing this. Judging is, at least from my perspective, never a good idea. In situations like this, it is crucial to found out what's going on, if the issue is a lack of social skills , or maybe a way of coping with stress? I would talk to my child about the situation and see if I was able to find out more, without any judgments, otherwise my child will not keep talking to me. Then I'd search for options so my child can learn new skills or new ways of dealing with stress. I'd also want to know if my child had any 'victims'. If this is the case, I'd like to speak to the victim and/or the parents/caregivers, so I can explain how I'm addressing the issue and to apologize."

<em><a href="http://quib.ly/qu/what-would-you-do-if-you-found-out-that-your-child-is-a-bully#answers#1878">~ Laura Fobler, Parent-Child Communication Expert: Quib.ly</a></em>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.12.03.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-39740096045" alt="23snaps; Is your child the bully?" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.12.03.png" width="217" height="280" /></a></p>
<em><strong>What should a parent be on the look out for to know whether their child is exhibiting bullying behaviour?</strong></em>

"Children who are bullying are highly unlikely to talk about their behaviour, either because they are afraid of your reaction or because they don’t believe that what they’re doing is wrong. As parents and carers, we hope that our children and those in our care can to talk to us if they are having problems, if they are in trouble or if something is making them scared or miserable. However, even if you have a good relationship with them this can be difficult. If you don't have a terribly easy relationship with your child and you find it difficult to talk to each other, you will need to be even more patient in your approach with them.

Often young people bully because they are being bullied and harassed in some way themselves. This may be at school of course, but it can also happen at home. This might be difficult to consider, but try and look at your family/extended family dynamics and see if there are any tense or troubling relationships. Bullying routinely goes on between siblings and other family members. It may also help you to look at reasons young people have given for bullying when interviewed:
<ul>
	<li>I'm angry</li>
	<li>I'm being bullied myself</li>
	<li>If I don't do it first, it will happen to me</li>
	<li>All my mates do it</li>
	<li>It makes me popular</li>
	<li>I'm lonely</li>
</ul>
Here are some lists of physical, emotional and behavioural clues that you may see in your child if he/she is bullying. They may help you to support your child if he/she is having a problem with bullying but has not yet been able to talk to you about it. By picking up on these clues, you can then raise the subject of bullying with your child.

<strong>Physical signs</strong>

Using physical strength/physical presence to intimidate, influence and impress other kids – this might be friends or younger brothers and sisters. For example, putting them in head and arm locks. This behaviour is more common in boys than girls. Children and young people, particularly boys, often play-fight and it is a mistake to assume that such behaviour is always evidence of bullying. However, be aware of body language and roles in these situations. Look to see if your child uses physical strength to humiliate other children or make them feel weak or powerless or if he/she is consistently picking on one or more other children, particularly if the body language of those children indicates that they are unhappy or scared and want the play-fight to stop. If this is the case, then it is likely that what is going on is bullying and you need to stop it and discourage your child from behaving in this way in future.

<strong>Emotional signs</strong>

A refusal or inability to empathise with others is common. You may notice that your child is unable or unwilling to put themselves in the shoes of a person who is being bullied and think about how the bullying might make that person feel. Young people who bully often say that it’s the victim’s fault for not standing up for themselves or that he/she should “learn to take a joke”. Often a bully will show an inability or refusal to accept responsibility for their actions. Children who bully invariably express the opinion that the responsibility for the bullying lies with the victim. Again, they tend to say that it is the victim’s fault for being weak or disrespectful, or for getting on their nerves. Bullies show a desire to be in control. Children who bully often seem to need to be in charge and can find it difficult to share leadership or co-operate with others. They may be able to work with others, but only on their terms.

<strong>Behavioural signs</strong>

Young people who bully have low self-esteem and bully so that they can make others do what they say and give themselves a sense of power and superiority. They often brag about their exploits and abilities to cover a low sense of self-worth. They show a tendency to relate to others in a negative way, e.g. making negative comments about other people’s appearance, intelligence, ability, family, behaviour, etc. This may include an intolerance of other cultures and lifestyles and the use of racist, sexist and homophobic language, e.g. using “gay” as a term of abuse. Lots of people talk about others in unflattering terms, in fact nearly everybody makes negative comments about other people sometimes, but if your child does this on a regular basis you have reason to be concerned. It is worth thinking honestly about the way that you talk about other people in front of your child as well.

Once again, a child who shows one or more of these indicators is not necessarily bullying, but they are displaying and supporting behaviours and attitudes that have a negative effect on themselves, their friends and potentially all the people that they live with. It is important that, as a parent and carer you try to challenge these behaviours, build up your child’s self-esteem and help them find ways of showing the world that they are valuable and worth taking notice of that don’t have a negative effect on others."

<a href="http://archive.beatbullying.org/dox/help/how-do-i-know-if-my-child-is-a-bully.html"><em>~ Liz Watson, Head of BeatBullying: BeatBullying</em></a>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.17.06.png"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-39740096047" alt="Screen Shot 2013-11-19 at 12.17.06" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Screen-Shot-2013-11-19-at-12.17.06.png" width="298" height="280" /></a></p>
<em><strong>What can I do to prevent my child from repeating this behaviour in the future?</strong></em>

"<strong>Take bullying seriously.</strong> Make sure your kids understand that you will not tolerate bullying at home or anywhere else. Establish rules about bullying and stick to them. If you punish your child by taking away privileges, be sure it's meaningful. For example, if your child bullies other kids via email, text messages, or a social networking site; dock phone or computer privileges for a period of time. If your child acts aggressively at home, with siblings or others, put a stop to it and teach more appropriate (and nonviolent) ways to react, like walking away.

<strong>Teach kids to treat others with respect and kindness.</strong> Teach your child that it is wrong to ridicule differences (e.g., race, religion, appearance, special needs, gender, economic status) and try to instill a sense of empathy for those who are different. Consider getting involved together in a community group where your child can interact with kids who are different.

<strong>Learn about your child's social life.</strong> Look for insight into the factors that may be influencing your child's behavior in the school environment (or wherever the bullying is occurring). Talk with parents of your child's friends and peers, teachers, guidance counselors, and the school principal. Do other kids bully? What about your child's friends? What kinds of pressures do the kids face at school? Talk to your kids about those relationships and about the pressures to fit in. Get them involved in activities outside of school so that they meet and develop friendships with other kids.

<strong>Encourage good behavior.</strong> Positive reinforcement can be more powerful than negative discipline. Catch your kids being good — and when they handle situations in ways that are constructive or positive, take notice and praise them for it.

<strong>Set a good example.</strong> Think carefully about how you talk around your kids and how you handle conflict and problems. If you behave aggressively — toward or in front of your kids — chances are they'll follow your example. Instead, point out positives in others, rather than negatives. And when conflicts arise in your own life, be open about the frustrations you have and how you cope with your feelings."

<a href="http://kidshealth.org/parent/emotions/behavior/no_bullying.html#"><em>~ D'Arcy Lyness, PhD, Child and Adolescent Psychologist: Kidshealth</em></a>

&nbsp;

As it's Anti-Bullying Week, now is a great time to address any bullying behaviour your child may be exhibiting. It can be really tough accepting your child's behaviour, but by being proactive and facing the issue head on, the situation is much more likely to be resolved in a way that is acceptable for all parties involved.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Start Building A Journal For Your Unborn Child</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-start-building-a-journal-for-your-unborn-child/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 22 Nov 2013 12:30:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096057</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[If you want to start documenting your little bub's precious memories whilst they are still in your belly, it can be easily done. Upload scan photos, snaps of the baby shower gifts, updates about check-ups and add it to their timeline ... nothing needs to be left our during this exciting time.

So let us talk you through setting up your unborn baby's journal ...

First you'll need to set up your own 23snaps account so you can manage your babies timeline. You can do this either on <a href="http://23snaps.com?utm_source=social&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=TOTW_unborn">23snaps.com</a> or on either our <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/id526481189?mt=8">iPhone/iPad app</a>, <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.snaps23.android&amp;referrer=af_tranid%3DBQCJ905WVM7C8ZF%26c%3Dnewsfeed%26pid%3Dwebsite">Android app</a> on <a href="http://apps.microsoft.com/windows/en-us/app/23snaps/8d8b50ab-fc02-49c5-a648-06b8fd586f9f">Windows 8 app</a>

<em><strong>On the website</strong>:</em>

Simply go to 23snaps.com and click on the orange <em>Signup</em> button in the top right corner. All you need to do is fill in the form with your name, email address and a password for the account (you also have the option of connecting via facebook) and you’re ready to go.

<img title="Image: /attachments/token/czhvdqcufyfrubn/?name=1.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/czhvdqcufyfrubn/?name=1.jpg" alt="1.jpg" width="300" />  <img title="Image: /attachments/token/nwrgeygsbyesqg5/?name=2.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/nwrgeygsbyesqg5/?name=2.jpg" alt="2.jpg" width="300" />

<strong><em>On the app:</em></strong>

Download 23snaps and open the app. Click on the <em>Sign Up </em>button on the left of the screen. All you need to do is fill in the form with your name, email address and a password for the account, then tap <em>Sign Up</em> again to complete the process.

<strong><em>                                     <img title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200191648/Register_1.png" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200191648/Register_1.png" alt="" width="200" />  <img title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200262967/Register_2.png" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200262967/Register_2.png" alt="" width="200" /></em></strong>

&nbsp;

Now, you just need to add your bump to your account.

<em><strong>On the website
</strong></em>

Click on <em>"Your Name"</em> on the Menu Tab at the top of the screen, then select <em>Family &amp; Friends</em>. Select the tab that says <em>Children</em> and then click on the green <em>Add a Child</em> button. Now all you have to do is add the name, date of birth, and gender of your child, but as your little one isn't here yet you could put a nickname and due date for now, then simply update the info as and when you know it. You can then add a profile picture, it could be of your ultrasound scan or baby bump, it’s entirely up to you. When you’re finished remember to click on the green <em>Add a Child</em> button again to ensure your child’s timeline is saved.

<img title="Image: /attachments/token/qawtabcj9yapssw/?name=1.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/qawtabcj9yapssw/?name=1.jpg" alt="1.jpg" width="300" />  <img title="Image: /attachments/token/frre6dqd33tykir/?name=2.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/frre6dqd33tykir/?name=2.jpg" alt="2.jpg" width="300" />

<img title="Image: /attachments/token/c12i4dustex7bkf/?name=3.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/c12i4dustex7bkf/?name=3.jpg" alt="3.jpg" width="300" />  <img title="Image: /attachments/token/ocvqfh3oyvwqnul/?name=4.jpg" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/attachments/token/ocvqfh3oyvwqnul/?name=4.jpg" alt="4.jpg" width="300" />

&nbsp;

<em><strong>On the app</strong></em>

Tap the <em>Menu</em> button and then select <em>Add your children</em>, then tap the green <em>Add a Child</em> button. Enter your child’s nickname, due date and gender, and choose a profile picture, then click <i>Submit </i>to complete the process.

<img title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200270413/Add_child_1.png" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200270413/Add_child_1.png" alt="" width="200" /> <img title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200263217/Add_child_2.png" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200263217/Add_child_2.png" alt="" width="200" /> <img title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200194366/Add_child_3.png" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200194366/Add_child_3.png" alt="" width="200" />

Now you're ready to go! You can start building a beautiful digital baby book including all of the precious moments that occur before your little one even arrives.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>We have removed the tags that were placed on top of the photos &amp; videos!</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/we-have-removed-the-tags-that-were-placed-on-top-of-the-photos-videos/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 26 Nov 2013 11:02:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096064</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Even with the very best of intentions occasionally parents can pick some questionable outfits for their children (90's flowered leggings anyone?). We may have made a questionable outfit choice for 23snaps in our last update so we've removed the child name and age tag on top of the photo. Sorry! No more flowered leggings, or distractions from your beautiful photos.

Although we completely hold our hands up to this error in judgement on our part, there were various reasons behind this decision in our design process ...

We wanted to highlight that the exact age of the child at the time the photo is taken is displayed with each post, as this is a feature that we love.

We also wanted to bring the attention of some of our less tech-savvy users to all of the other aspects of the app. We know that most of the parents who create the content on 23snaps are pretty good with their tech gadgets, but for some of their family members we wanted to make it even easier to navigate to all the beautiful content shared with them on 23snaps. We didn't want anyone to miss out on the Calendar and Gallery views, or the chronological timeline of your children's lives, just because they were unaware of the option. This is why we redesigned this layout to make it more obvious that this was a functioning button, and included it in the preview image so that it wouldn't be missed.

However, the feedback we have received about all of 23snaps in general is that the photos that you share with your loved ones are the most important thing, and we would never want to do anything to detract from your enjoyment of scrolling through the app and looking at your beautiful photos. So we hold up our hands to our mistake, and we have moved the button! You can now enjoy your photos with nothing in the way, and if you want to tap into your child's timeline simply click on the button in it's new location just underneath your photo.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/No-tag-over-image.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096070" alt="23snaps; Tag location update" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/No-tag-over-image-926x1024.png" width="360" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/No-tag-over-image-21.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096072" alt="23snaps; Tag location update" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/No-tag-over-image-21-679x1024.png" width="260" /></a>

We are always changing and trying to perfect the app, and we hope you enjoy the re-design even more now that we've made some tweaks.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip Of The Week: Posting Content Privately</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-posting-content-privately/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 29 Nov 2013 12:00:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096086</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[You can now <strong>upload photos, videos, and updates privately</strong> for just you and your partner. These updates will be visible to both you and your partner, but will not appear in the timeline or on the child's pages for any of your other connections.

All you need to do is begin the process of uploading your photo, video or status as normal (NB. this feature is not available when posting multiple photos), but before you hit <i>Publish</i> make sure that the visibility slider is in the locked position.

Each time you post this will be reset to the public default.

<img style="border: 1px solid black;" title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200226386/Private_Posting_1.PNG" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200226386/Private_Posting_1.PNG" alt="" width="300" />     <img style="border: 1px solid black;" title="Image: /hc/en-us/article_attachments/200226396/Private_Posting_2.PNG" src="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/article_attachments/200226396/Private_Posting_2.PNG" alt="" width="300" height="533" />]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>How To Take The Best Family Photos Over The Holiday Season</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/how-to-take-the-best-family-photos-over-the-holiday-season/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Nov 2013 04:00:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096094</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[With the Holiday season well and truly upon us, it's time to start celebrating! These moments that you spend with family are too precious not to capture forever in a photograph, so we've got a few simple tips to help make the most of the opportunity and take the best photos of your family over the holidays.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096095" style="margin-left: 5px;" alt="Family Holiday photos 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-1-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096096" style="margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px;" alt="Family Holiday photos 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-2-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096097" alt="Family Holiday photos 3" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-3-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-4.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096098" style="margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px;" alt="Family Holiday photos 4" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Family-Holiday-photos-4-150x150.jpg" width="150" height="150" /></a>

1.<strong> Take lots of photographs</strong> until you're happy with the shot: professional photographers always do. Review the images as you go, checking they're sharp and haven't caught any frightening micro-expressions which may be invisible to the naked eye (the mid-blink is not a great look). You can always delete duplicates later.

2. <strong>Be creative with your compositions</strong>: shoot from an interesting angle, get in close or click discreetly to capture your family unaware. Experiment. Try shooting through a coloured glass bauble or outside against wintery trees. No firing squads.

3. <strong>Be aware of different angles</strong>: if you are photographing children, shoot from their height on your knees or stomach. Don't tell them to "smile for the camera"; make them laugh instead, or try shooting candidly.

4. <strong>Use natural daylight</strong> if at all possible be gentle with flash. Experiment with your camera settings to find a compromise.

5. <strong>Make sure your batteries are fully charged</strong> and there's enough space on your memory card. Feeling like you're just about to take the perfect shot only to have your camera die, or run out of space, can be immensely frustrating ... and no one wants extra stress!!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Could your social media posts be putting your family at risk over the Holidays?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/could-your-social-media-posts-be-putting-your-family-at-risk-over-the-holidays/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Dec 2013 14:39:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096148</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[For most people, the holidays are a time of increased social network activity. People posts about their plans for the holidays, upload photo after photo of their family enjoying the festivities, or post what kind of fabulous gifts they’re buying and receiving. We love this time of year, and we think it's definitely a time for sharing, but it is important to do so in a way that won't put yourselves, your families, or your homes at risk.

We have just a couple of simple ways that you can make sure you're not exposing your family to any unnecessary dangers over the holidays.

<strong>Don't advertise leaving your house unattended.</strong>

<strong><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-03-at-10.55.09.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096149 alignnone" style="margin-left: 50px;" alt="Screen Shot 2013-12-03 at 10.55.09" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-03-at-10.55.09.png" width="383" height="203" /></a></strong><strong style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/red-cross.png"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096155 alignnone" alt="red cross" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/red-cross-150x150.png" width="150" height="150" /></a></strong>

It's true that most people will read this in a perfectly innocent way. However, some opportunistic individual could interpret this as "I've just spent loads of money on new expensive devices that I will be leaving in my unoccupied house all weekend ... come and get them!" Is it really worth coming home from your delightful weekend away to discover that a Grinch has stolen Christmas, all for the sake of one tweet? If you can't resist sharing what you've been up to (and why should you?), being a little cryptic could really help protect your home.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-03-at-11.01.14.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096151 alignnone" style="margin-left: 50px;" alt="Screen Shot 2013-12-03 at 11.01.14" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-03-at-11.01.14.png" width="383" height="170" /></a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/green-tick.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096154" alt="green tick" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/green-tick-150x150.png" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<p style="text-align: left;">Those people that you really know and trust will know what you're talking about, but you're no longer advertising the fact that your home will be empty for the next few days.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Keep Family Photos Private.</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">With the whole family around you, it's understandable that you will want to capture cherished memories on film. But whilst everyone may be happy to be included in your photos, they may be less impressed about having them posted online. Whilst you may deem an image of kids unwrapping gifts to be entirely innocent, some of the people captured in that snap may be uncomfortable with it being online. Remember, some people shy away from the thought of having their image online, because once it's out there, it is very hard to get it back.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Many parents are also uncomfortable with the idea of photos of their children being online. The thought of creating a public digital footprint for their child before their old enough to have a say in the matter can be unappealing. This sometimes leads to parents being determined to keep their little one's likeness away from sites such as Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Instagram-Holidays.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096166" style="margin-left: 71px;" alt="Instagram Holidays" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Instagram-Holidays-576x1024.png" width="300" /></a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/red-cross.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096155" alt="red cross" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/red-cross-150x150.png" width="150" height="150" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">To keep your loved ones safe and happy, use a private social network like 23snaps. We recommend creating a private network for your immediate family so you can share your personal photos and memories without worrying about who’s getting the opportunity to peek. You can rest easy knowing that 23snaps was specifically designed to keep family photos safe and private, preventing unwanted viewers from gaining access whilst still allowing your selected family to enjoy your precious memories.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23snaps-Holidays.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096163" style="margin-left: 71px;" alt="23snaps Holidays" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23snaps-Holidays-576x1024.png" width="300" /></a><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096154" alt="green tick" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/green-tick-150x150.png" width="150" height="150" /></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">“He sees you when you’re sleeping, he knows when you’re awake" ... let's just make sure that this privilege is is only awarded to Santa!</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Professional Photography Course from Barrett &amp; Coe</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/professional-photography-course-from-barrett-coe/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 04 Dec 2013 10:49:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096129</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.barrettandcoe.co.uk/photography-courses/" target="_blank"><img alt="BC_logo reversed_cmyk" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/BC-logo-reversed_rgb-1024x417.jpg" width="640" height="260" /></a>We've teamed up with Barrett &amp; Coe Photography Studios to provide an amazing, free, family portrait shoot with framed 8”x6” photograph of you favourite shot (usually priced at £160)*. We're very excited about this amazing offer, but that's not all Barrett &amp; Coe can do for you! They also run <strong>fantastic professional photography courses</strong>*. Discover contemporary, reportage and spontaneous photography from the masters.

Barrett &amp; Coe offer both <strong>Wedding photography</strong> courses and <strong>Portrait photography</strong> courses, through which you can earn recognised photography qualifications. You will be taught:
<ul>
	<li>How to organise and structure a photography session or wedding</li>
	<li>How to take award-winning photographs</li>
	<li>Digital workflow, image editing and retouching and how to create cutting edge products</li>
</ul>
You will also benefit from individual mentoring throughout your course, a practical photography assignment and the opportunity (where possible) to accompany a Barrett &amp; Coe photographer on a wedding and observe portrait photography sessions and viewings

Once you have completed your 4-6 months of training you will take a final practical and written exam. Upon passing each student is awarded a Barrett &amp; Coe Diploma, an <strong>industry recognised qualification</strong>. Should you want to make photography your full-time (or part-time) career, Barrett &amp; Coe <strong>will even help you get your business up and running</strong>. In the 18 months alone they have had 20 course graduates start their own successful photography studios.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-11.jpg"><img alt="Barrett &amp; Coe Photography Courses" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-11-150x150.jpg" width="155" height="155" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-16.jpg"><img alt="Barrett &amp; Coe Photography Courses" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-16-150x150.jpg" width="155" height="155" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-18.jpg"><img alt="Barrett &amp; Coe Photography Courses" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-18-150x150.jpg" width="155" height="155" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-33.jpg"><img alt="Barrett &amp; Coe Photography Courses" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/23s-33-150x150.jpg" width="155" height="155" /></a>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Build Your 23snaps Photobook with a Title, Names, Ages, and Photo Descriptions.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-build-your-23snaps-photobook-with-a-title-names-ages-and-photo-descriptions/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Dec 2013 12:00:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096181</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We're very pleased to have been able to build this option into our photobook printing service so quickly! So many of you asked for the ability to <strong>include text in your photobooks</strong>, and we love to give you what you want. Now you can <strong>order a completely comprehensive journal</strong> with all of your little one's photos, as well as their age at the time each photo was taken and a description of the day.

To order one of our redesigned photo journals, you will have to head over to the <a href="http://23snaps.com/order/create">23snaps website</a> (we're in the process if building it into the app ... and hopefully it will ready soon!).

Once you have logged into your account, click on the <i>Prints &amp; Books</i> option in the menu bar at the top of the screen. Select the option to <em>Order Books</em>. To create your order; click on the <em>Add Photos to Order</em> button and decide whether you want to start with your own photos or those that have been shared with you (remember: you can use both for one order).

Once you have selected at least the minimum 24 images you wish to use, click <em>Add Selected Photos</em> in the bottom right corner of the screen. You can now view a digital preview of your photobook by clicking on <em>Preview Book </em>in the top right corner of the screen.
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Book-7.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-39740096182 aligncenter" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Book-7-1024x593.jpg" alt="23snaps TOTW" width="400" /></a></p>
This is where you will have the option to add text to your photobook order. Simply click on the <i>Edit Book Layout </i>button.
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.01.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740096183 aligncenter" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.01-1024x564.png" alt="23snaps TOTW" width="400" /></a></p>
Enter your chosen title in the text box provided, but remember it can only be up to 50 characters. You can also decide which text to include by either ticking or unticking the following options:
<ul>
	<li>the author's name and the date the photo was taken</li>
	<li>the photo's description</li>
	<li>the children in the photo and their ages when the photo was taken</li>
</ul>
<em>(Please note that these options will automatically be included unless you decide otherwise)</em>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.17.png"><img class=" wp-image-39740096184 aligncenter" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.17.png" alt="23snaps TOTW" width="400" /></a></p>
Once you have made your choices and you are happy with your order, click <em>Place Order.</em>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.43.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096185 aligncenter" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-11-06-at-15.37.43.png" alt="23snaps TOTW" width="400" height="221" /></a></p>]]></content:encoded>

		<wp:ping_status>closed</wp:ping_status>

	<item>
				<title>Online Safety: Teaching kids safe practise on social media</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/online-safety-teaching-kids-safe-practise-on-social-media/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 Dec 2013 15:35:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096192</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Teen-Social-Media.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096194" alt="Teen Social Media" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Teen-Social-Media.jpg" width="640" /></a>Learning how to use social media in a safe way is something that all children (and most adults) still need to learn. When your children get a bit older, they are going to want to set up their own social media profiles. Social networks like Facebook and Twitter have become the primary way for a lot of people to communicate, and it is inevitable that your children will want to be involved. Whilst we wouldn't recommend ever agreeing to let your child join a social network before the legal age of 13, it is a good idea to get involved when they reach the minimum age restriction and help them get started. If you refuse to let them join their friends on sites like Facebook then it is very likely that they will just go ahead and do what they want behind your back. By getting involved from the start, you can help your child learn how they can protect themselves and why doing so is of utmost importance. It will also give you the opportunity to teach them what you consider acceptable behaviour and how they should manage their digital presence.

<strong>Explain that when you post something online, it will be there forever</strong>. Anything that is posted online can become available to the public. Teach your children to use the privacy settings to their advantage, but never to rely on them. If they want something to remain private, it is best not to upload it to the internet at all, as once it's online there is no guarantee that all traces of it can be deleted.

<strong>Let them know that bullying is unacceptable under any circumstances</strong>. When a child turns to social media as a forum for hurtful speech, the risks are unmeasurable. Not only could that child cause severe emotional distress to another human being, but they could also face serious criminal prosecution. They also need to be made aware that if they are on the receiving end of any bullying behaviour, that they need to be able to come to you. There are ways of reporting and dealing with such conduct and your child needs to be mature enough to be able to ask for help.

<strong>Tell them NEVER to post confidential information online</strong>. Young people seem to be particularly vulnerable to this error in judgement. Regardless of whether they believe that they have adequate privacy filters, all it would take was one person who can see their content to share that to their own public profile and whatever private information was posted becomes available to billions of people. It is definitely worth stressing to your child what information is not ok to post online, this would include:
<ul>
	<li>Full Name</li>
	<li>Address</li>
	<li>Telephone Number</li>
	<li>Email Address</li>
	<li>Social Security/National Insurance Number</li>
	<li>Bank Details</li>
	<li>Date of Birth</li>
</ul>
<strong>Explain that posting emotional statuses is inadvisable</strong>. It's inevitable that your teenager will experience at least one moment of anger, upset or outrage during the delightful emotional roller coaster that is puberty  and it's human nature to react without thinking through the consequences. However, whenever possible, they should take a moment to imagine how an emotionally charged social media post could affect the feelings, safety and well-being of those around them. Posting an angry tweet in the heat of the moment may feel cathartic, but the momentary pleasure gained from writing it isn't worth the potential harm it could create.

<strong>Advise them never to post specific location related posts</strong>. Checking-in has become a favourite of many social media users, it allows them to show people the cool places that they get to go and the fun lives that they lead. But it also makes it very easy for people to track you down. If your child is without adult supervision, they should never post their real-time location online.

It is down to every family to decide on the best approach for their children when first engaging on social media, but ensuring that your children understand appropriate conduct and good practise is essential as it can prevent numerous disasters later on.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Edit Post Details in a Batch Upload.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-edit-post-details-in-a-batch-upload/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 13 Dec 2013 12:00:19 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096207</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We hope you're enjoying the ability to post up to 15 pictures at one time with our multiple posting functionality. It was a feature that you told us you wanted and so we built it ... especially for you! This feature will hopefully be saving you loads of time when it comes to building your child's timeline, especially if your child is that little bit older and you want to back date their posts. But did you know that you can also add descriptions to your photos, change the dates and even add them to specific collections whilst uploading them all at once?

Here's how:

<strong>On the 23snaps website</strong>

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Edit-Multiple-Uploads-web.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-39740096208 alignnone" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Edit-Multiple-Uploads-web-1024x506.png" alt="Edit Multiple Uploads 23snaps Website" width="640" height="316" /></a>

Once you have selected the photos you wish to post, you will be taken to the Edit screen, where you have the ability to make the changes mentioned earlier. Whilst we endeavour to offer the dame functionality across all platforms that 23snaps is available on, unfortunately it is not yet possible to add photos to a collection during this process on the website. However, you do have the option to enter individual descriptions for each photo and also alter the date for each photo.

-  To enter a description, simply click on the text box next to the corresponding photo and enter your text.

-  To alter the date, simply click on the date currently showing beneath each image, and select your preferred date from the Calendar.

This information will automatically be included in your post when you click <em>Submit Photos.</em>

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Edit-Multiple-Uploads-app1.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-39740096212" style="margin-right: 10px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Edit-Multiple-Uploads-app1.png" alt="Edit Multiple Uploads 23snaps App" width="320" /></a>
<strong>On the 23snaps app</strong>

Once you have selected the photos you wish to post, you will again be taken to the Edit screen but this time it looks a little different. Here you have the ability to add you photos to a Collection of your choice, and to add individual descriptions to each photo.

- To add the entire batch oh photo to a collection, simply click on the <em>Add to collections </em>button. Then simply select the collection(s) of you choice and click <em>Done.</em>

- To enter a description, simply tap on the words <em>Tap to add description ...</em> and then enter your text and click <em>Done.</em>

This information will automatically be included in your post when you click <em>Finish.</em> <em> </em>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Create Photobooks From Whole Collections and Calendar Months</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-create-photobooks-from-whole-collections-and-calendar-months/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 20 Dec 2013 12:00:40 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096232</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Did you know that you can actually <strong>create 23snaps photobooks from both collections, and months,</strong> within the <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/23snaps-family-journal-private/id526481189?mt=8">iPhone app</a>? While this functionality isn't yet available on the website (don't worry we know it's an important addition and we hope to add it soon!) you can add an entire collection or calendar month to a book order in just a couple of clicks.

If you're building a Christmas Collection within the app and you want to have that beautiful selection of photos compiled into an album you can hold in your hand, all you have to do is open that collection and <strong>tap the overlapping photo icon</strong> in the top right corner of the screen. The entire Collection will be added to your print order in chronological order without any more effort on your part! If you want to add more than 1 collection to your order, simply go back and repeat the process.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Collection-1.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096229 alignnone ;" style="margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 15px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Collection-1.png" alt="TOTW Print from Collection 1" width="300" height="533" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Collection-2.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096230 alignnone" style="margin-right: 10px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Collection-2-576x1024.png" alt="TOTW Print from Collection 2" width="300" height="533" /></a>

&nbsp;

It is also possible to add an entire months worth of photos to your photobook, simply open the month you wish to use on either your own timeline, your families timeline, or and individual child's timeline. Then once again you just need to tap the overlapping photo icon in the top corner. The<strong> entire month will be added to your order, in chronological order</strong>, and if you wish to add another month, simply repeat the process.

&nbsp;

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Calendar-1.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096226" style="margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 15px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Calendar-1-576x1024.png" alt="TOTW Print from Calendar 1" width="300" height="533" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Calendar-2.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096227" style="margin-right: 10px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Print-from-Calendar-2-578x1024.png" alt="TOTW Print from Calendar 2" width="300" height="0" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

There's no catch, no costs - simply the option to purchase additional prints from your Barrett &amp; Coe photographer at the end of your free session. 				<title>Merry Christmas from 23snaps</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/merry-christmas-from-23snaps/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 25 Dec 2013 12:30:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096262</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://23snaps.com"><img class="alignnone" alt="" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-CLd0pBryYWE/Uq8rAD9xOfI/AAAAAAAABM4/g_Aw3BgJmxI/w512-h307-no/snowman-TWINKLE.gif" width="640" /></a>
<p style="text-align: center">We hope you have a wonderful day, filled with special moments and memories to capture on camera … unwrapping presents, pulling a cracker or tucking into some turkey, there are literally hundreds of moments waiting to be snapped and shared with the ones you love.</p>
<p style="text-align: center">We would just like to wish you all a very Merry Christmas.</p>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Android Video Hacks</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-android-video-hacks/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 03 Jan 2014 12:30:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096270</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Many Android devices are well known for taking very high quality photos and videos, which is great! But there is a downside ... it makes the video files absolutely enormous. On 23snaps, the maximum file size for a video upload is 20mb, this is to enable you to quickly and easily upload your content wherever you are. We want to show you how to get the most out of you Android video camera within this limit using tools that are already built into your device.

<strong>Trimming a video</strong>

Locate the video that you plan to upload to 23snaps in your device's gallery* (go to the gallery directly, there is no need to open 23snaps yet). If you tap the screen you will see various options appear, select the <em>Trim </em>functionality. You are then able to drag the sliders to highlight the shorter section of video you wish to use. Once you're done making your selection, simply click <em>Done</em>. This process will save a new copy of your video. You will still have a copy of the full length original video, so there is no need to duplicate your file first.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-4.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096274" alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 4" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-4-300x168.png" width="317" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-5.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096275" alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 5" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-5-300x168.png" width="317" /></a>

Although it is not possible to see the size of the cropped section of video during the trimming process, you are able to check the size of the file first and you can figure out how much to trim accordingly. For example, if you video is 60 seconds long and 30mb, you will need to reduce the file size by 1/3. This means that you will need to reduce the video length by about the same amount. In this example that would mean trimming off 20 seconds to leave a video 40 seconds long. To find this information just tap on the <em>"Options"</em> button on your device, then select <em>Details</em>.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-6.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096276" style="margin-left: 107px" alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 6" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-6-576x1024.png" width="210" /> </a><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-71.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-39740096285" style="margin-right: 107px" alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 7" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-71-576x1024.png" width="210" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Reducing Video Quality</strong>

It is also possible to restrict the quality of the video that you record on an Android, this is turn reduces the file size, but you do need to remember to do this before you press record! Open up your device's camera* and on the right hand side of the screen you will see various options, tap on the gear icon. Then select the video camera icon and select <em>Limit for MMS</em>. This will reduce the quality of the video that you record on this occasion, but once the camera is closed, it will revert to the high quality default.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-1.png"><img alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 1" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-1-576x1024.png" width="210" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-2.png"><img alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 2" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-2-576x1024.png" width="210" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-3.png"><img alt="TOTW 23snaps Android Video Hacks 3" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/TOTW-Android-Video-Hacks-3-576x1024.png" width="210" /></a>

&nbsp;

Either of these options should enabled you to upload a much larger selection of your <a href="https://23snaps.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/200264568-Uploading-photos-videos-and-updates-to-23snaps#video">videos to 23snaps</a> from your Android device.

<em>* The screenshots were taken using a Galaxy S4, the layout of your options may differ slightly from those pictured. </em>]]></content:encoded>

				<title>Our Christmas Gift to You ... the 23snaps Time Machine.</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/our-christmas-gift-to-you-the-23snaps-time-machine/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 21 Dec 2013 02:00:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096290</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[In 2013, we've seen the children we love grow and change so much. So we've been working on something special this Christmas.

As our gift to you, we are proud to unveil the <b>23snaps Time Machine</b>.

The Time Machine helps you discover photos and videos from the past, and enjoy content in 23snaps that you may have forgotten.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-20-at-15.24.45.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096297" alt="Screen Shot 2013-12-20 at 15.24.45" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-20-at-15.24.45.png" width="630" height="476" /></a>&nbsp;

Make sure you've updated to the latest version of 23snaps on <strong><a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=twitter&amp;c=timemachine">iOS</a></strong> or <strong><a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/com.snaps23.android?pid=twitter&amp;c=timemachine">Android</a></strong>. Choose the new Time Machine option from the menu and <strong>Shake the phone</strong> to rediscover the moments and memories you've saved and shared, or have been shared with you!

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Tip of the Week: Downloading 23snaps to Older iOS Devices</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-tip-of-the-week-downloading-23snaps-to-older-ios-devices/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 10 Jan 2014 12:00:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096309</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096321" alt="23snaps iPad Mini" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/photo-2-3_ipadmini_white_portrait1-214x300.png" width="214" height="300" /> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/photo_iphone5s_silver_portrait1.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096319" alt="23snaps iPhone" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/photo_iphone5s_silver_portrait1-152x300.png" width="152" height="300" /></a><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096320" alt="23snaps iPad" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/photo-1-3_ipad4_white_portrait1-269x300.png" width="269" height="300" />

With many people receiving new tech for Christmas, lots of their friends and relatives have been lucky enough to inherit their older devices, such as a 1st Generation iPad. Unfortunately Apple seem to have forgotten about the thousands of people that still use these older devices, as demonstrated by the fact that their newest operating system isn't compatible with this particular device.

As an app developer, we need to develop along with the operating systems of companies like Apple, but we don't want to leave those of you with slightly older devices out in the cold! So whilst our most recent app update does require iOS7, <strong>you can still download the latest compatible version of 23snaps for your device</strong> even if you are unable to update your operating system.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Older-iOS-Version-Screenshot_ipad4_white_portrait1.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096311 alignleft" alt="Older iOS Version Screenshot_ipad4_white_portrait" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Older-iOS-Version-Screenshot_ipad4_white_portrait1-796x1024.png" width="300" height="386" /></a>

When you go to the <a href="http://bit.ly/1a3ABbn">App Store</a>, you should always be given the option to <strong>download the latest compatible version</strong> of the 23snaps app. However we've discovered a slight glitch in Apple's systems that will prevent you from downloading this version of the app unless you have downloaded 23snaps in the past. But don't worry! we have a couple of work arounds that are tried and tested ...

If you are new to 23snaps (welcome!) you can get past this issue in 1 of 2 ways.

1) If you have access to a <strong>newer Apple device</strong>, use it to log into your iTunes account and download the latest version of 23snaps first. Once the app has been downloaded from your account once, you will be able to gain access to the last compatible version on your iPad.

2) Ask a friend or family member that also uses the 23snaps app to <strong>sign in to their iTunes account</strong> on your iPad and download the app on your behalf. This will not affect their 23snaps app or account in any way. Once the app is installed on your iPad, they can log out of their iTunes account. Your app will not be linked with theirs.

We've tested both of these processes and they worked perfectly for us, but if you do experience any issues, just drop us an email at <a href="mailto:support@23snaps.com">support@23snaps.com</a>, and we'll do our best to find another solution, specifically for you!]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>23snaps Introduces Stories - The Newest Way to Share Online</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/23snaps-introduces-stories-the-newest-way-to-share-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Mar 2014 15:23:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096384</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Sarahs-Birthday-Blog-eg.png"><img class="wp-image-39740096385 alignright" style="margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;" alt="Sarah's Birthday Blog eg" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Sarahs-Birthday-Blog-eg.png" width="162" height="1200" /></a></p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://www.23snaps.com/activity/story" target="_blank"><strong>We are so thrilled to announce our latest family feature, “Stories”</strong></a>. It is a brand new type of post that allows parents and families to quickly and easily combine photos and text into beautiful multimedia vignettes and post them to their Newsfeed alongside traditional photos and status updates.</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr">Our Head of Product Meaghan says of Stories, “They take family sharing to whole new level by <strong>allowing natural storytelling parents to use an unlimited combination of photos and text to share a single narrative from beginning to end</strong>. Parents are then able to share their favourite stories about their children’s lives with loved ones.”</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr">We were completely inspired by the fact that we think it takes more than one photo or comment to tell the best family stories. We found out that up to 40% of mothers blog in some form, which indicated the desire for parents to escape the constraints placed by existing social network content formats.</p>
&nbsp;
<p dir="ltr">Providing another solution for families to keep even the the least tech-savvy family members up to date with all of the most important family moments is another fantastic benefit of this cool new type of post.</p>
&nbsp;

Stories are now available on iPhone, iPad, Android and the 23snaps website. To start building your own family's Stories, <strong>update 23 snaps now</strong> and join in with our brand new story telling experience!

&nbsp;

<a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/id526481189?pid=blog&amp;c=stories"><em><strong>Update iOS</strong></em></a>

&nbsp;

<a href="http://app.appsflyer.com/com.snaps23.android?pid=blog&amp;c=stories"><em><strong>Update Android</strong></em></a>

&nbsp;

For help with how to get started, check out our handy helpdesk.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

				<title>Vote for 23snaps to present at TNW Europe 2014</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/39740096430/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 16 Apr 2014 15:00:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096430</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://thenextweb.com/boost/"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096431" alt="Screen Shot 2014-04-16 at 10.59.24" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Screen-Shot-2014-04-16-at-10.59.24.png" width="649" height="151" /></a>

We're very excited to be up for the chance of winning a spot to present 23snaps on stage at the <strong><a href="http://thenextweb.com/conference/europe/startups/boost">The Next Web Boost Conference</a></strong> on the 24th of April, but we need your help! The top 10 companies, as voted for by the public, will win a spot. We'd love to have the opportunity to spread the word about 23snaps to lots of families across Europe.

If you love the app as much as we do, please <strong><a href="//thenextweb.com/boost/">vote for 23snaps</a></strong> to win.

It only takes 2 clicks, and you'll be making us very very happy indeed.

	<item>
				<title>DIY Halloween Costume Ideas Perfect for Families </title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/diy-halloween-costume-ideas-perfect-for-families/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 12 Oct 2014 16:26:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rachell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096602</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">To help you get ready for Halloween, we've rounded up some of our favorite ideas for DIY costumes that will make your Halloween celebration even more fun for the whole family this year! Decorating the house with lights and scary accessories, carving some Jack-o'-lanterns and watching the kids counting the hours to the trick or treat day are some of the moments that make this day so special for families. But there is nothing more important (and fun) than choosing the costume!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">To ensure hours of fun and entertainment for the kids, a great idea is to create your own costumes at home with the help of the whole family. We have found a brilliant selection of costume ideas used by families that really know how to nail the art of DIY! From super heroes to Lego figures, there is an option to suit all tastes. You can click on each picture for further information and a step-by-step guide on how to make the costumes yourself.</p>

<h3></h3>
<h3>1- The Superhero Family</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Super hero costumes are always a great idea! Not only for kids, but they are great for parents too. Especially if they are as simple to make as these ones from 'The Incredibles"!</p>
<a href="http://freshlycompleted.blogspot.co.uk/2011/09/incredibles.html" target="_blank"> <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096866" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/incredibles-2.jpg" alt="incredibles 2" width="467" /></a>

Source: <a href="http://freshlycompleted.blogspot.co.uk/2011/09/incredibles.html" target="_blank">Freshly Completed</a>
<h3></h3>
<h3>2- The Cavemen Family</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This idea will please the more wild and fun families! Help your children travel back in time, straight to the prehistoric age. They will love to feel that they just came back from the Natural History Museum! As you can see, these costumes work for any age or gender, it's very easy to make and who doesn't like to get a little dirty sometimes?</p>
<a href="http://andreasnotebook.com/2012/09/handmade-costume-series-diy-caveman-costume-tutorial.html" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096867" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Cavemen-Family-Costume-idea-23snaps.jpg" alt="Cavemen Family Costume idea - 23snaps" width="467" /></a>

Source: <a href="http://andreasnotebook.com/2012/09/handmade-costume-series-diy-caveman-costume-tutorial.html”&quot;" target="_blank">Andrea's Notebook</a>
<h3></h3>
<h3>3- The Care Bears Family</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">What a great way to revive the parents' childhood memories, whilst introducing the kids to the awesome Care Bears! Kids will love the bright colors and bear ears on their hoods. Let your kids draw or paint the care bear symbols for the jumpers and to make your costumes even more unique.</p>
<a href="http://seevanessacraft.com/2012/10/20-crafty-days-of-halloween-no-sew-care-bear-costumes/" target="_blank"><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/9b67ada337010b3aafd6eaedf049c4ea.jpg" alt="width=467" /></a>

Source: <a href="http://seevanessacraft.com/2012/10/20-crafty-days-of-halloween-no-sew-care-bear-costumes" target="_blank">See Vanessa Craft</a>
<h3></h3>
<h3>4- The Candy Family</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Who doesn't like Candy? It's what trick or treating is all about! Turn each member of your family into their favorite sweet with just a little felt. Cute, creative and not too difficult to make. Just be prepared to get hungry while making the costumes!</p>
<a href="http://www.kristendukephotography.com/i-made-it-to-crafting-with-the-stars-round-2/" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096881" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/sweet-costumes-23snaps.jpg" alt="sweet costumes 23snaps" width="460" height="625" /></a>

Source: <a href="http://www.kristendukephotography.com/i-made-it-to-crafting-with-the-stars-round-2" target="_blank">Kristen Duken Photography</a>
<h3></h3>
<h3>5- The Lego Family</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">A classic, Lego is passing through generations and resisting the barriers of time! Parents used to love Legos when they were kids, nowadays not so much when they see the hundreds of Lego pieces dropped on the floor by their own kids, all around the house. This idea may require some extra work, but it will be definitely be worth it once the whole family is out of the house looking completely amazing.</p>
<a href="http://www.costume-works.com/lego_family.html" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096876" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/lego_family-23snaps.jpg" alt="lego_family 23snaps" width="467" /></a>

Source: <a href="http://www.costume-works.com/lego_family.html" target="_blank">Costume Works</a>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">We hope we've been able to inspire you, and help to make this Halloween unforgettable for your family. Don't forget to capture beautiful photos and videos of all your trick or treating  moments using <a href="http://www.23snaps.com”"> 23snaps</a>, the private social network and online journal for families!</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Online Family Album: Inheriting A Family Legacy</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/online-family-album-inheriting-a-family-legacy/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 01 Oct 2014 13:30:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096691</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">As a child, it can be hard to ever imagine your parents as children. When you were small, they were grown. As you aged, so did they. That inescapable age gap makes it hard to ever think of them as being younger than their current age. Looking at old photos of your parents as children is really one of the only ways to convince yourself that they didn't just spring into existence as fully grown adults. When you do find time to root through the dusty old photo albums; hilarity ensues, as you get to see all of the hideous outfits and ridiculous hair cuts inflicted on them by their own parents. These family albums are a wonderful legacy to inherit, they'll allow your family, and future generations, to look back and experience all of the wonderful memories that parents, grandparents, and even great grandparents created oh so long ago.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">With the prevalence of digital cameras, smartphones and tablets, the number of photos we take every day has increased dramatically. According to <a target="_blank">Yahoo's estimates</a>, more than 880 billion photos will be taken during 2014, that compares to the <a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/hunterschwarz/how-many-photos-have-been-taken-ever-6zgv#189jlfx" target="_blank">approximately 86 billion</a> photos that were taken in the year 2000. It's probably safe to assume that a good percentage of that number will be photos of smiling children taken by their doting parents. However, as it becomes easier and easier to whip out your camera and snap away, what is becoming of the hundreds, if not thousands, of photos we all take? Until fairly recently, if you wanted to take a photo you would capture the moment on an analogue camera, then amble off to the nearest photo developing shop to see how the photo turned out. Those photos would then be stored in an album on your bookshelf, easily accessible to anyone that was in the mood to reminisce. Now we take so many photos that the idea of sitting down and organising them all can become quite a daunting prospect.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">In a <a href="http://www.harrisinteractive.com/vault/Keepy%20Survey%20Release_final.pdf" target="_blank">recent poll of 250 parents</a> of children under 10, over 50% said that they have tons of photos/videos of their children, but haven’t done anything with them to keep them for the future. They have not organised their photos due to the sheer number of images they have stored, and the amount of time and effort it will take. A further 51% said that they wished they'd made more of a note of what was happening in the photo or video at the time it was taken, in order to better remember the moment.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">So, that leads me to ask the question;  what will happen when our children's children want to experience the enjoyment that flipping through our parents childhood photo albums gave us? They'll be told to log in to the Cloud, to sift through thousands of unorganised photos that were taken and forgotten. Not much of a family legacy, huh?</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Creating a tangible, if still digital, family album that your children, and their children, can inherit is something we shouldn't forget about in the increasingly technological time in which we live. There are various ways this can be done; you could create a Flickr account, and break the photos into albums. You can try MyFamilyHeritage.com, the genealogy  network that lets you create your own family tree. Or, you could give 23snaps a try. 23snaps enables the parents or guardians of each child to create both a family profile, and a dedicated timeline for their kids. You can easily save photos &amp; videos (with descriptions!), Stories, text updates and height &amp; weight measurements to your child's timeline, all of which are automatically chronologized for you based on the timestamp in the media file or the date the entry was created. In the future, your child will be able to inherit their own timeline, and create profiles for their own children. Your family's timeline will become a never ending family journal that can span generations. Whilst it's great that we're embracing the ease of snapping photos that new technology brings, lets not forget some of the wonderful family traditions of the past. Creating a photographic legacy that can be passed down through your family will bring joy to laughter to every member of your family, even those that aren't even born yet.</p>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://awkwardfamilyphotos.com/">AFP</a></i>]]></content:encoded>
