	<item>
				<title>Child-Proofing Your Phone and Tablet</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/child-proofing-your-phone-and-tablet/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 05 Oct 2014 15:30:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096698</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Do you regularly let your kids play on your phone or tablet? Have you put any <strong>child-proof measures</strong> in place? If not, you should. We promise it will make your life SO MUCH EASIER.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">As a parent, you must have lost count of the number of times your child has asked to play on your phone. It sometimes seems to be one of the first things kids learn how to say! But as children are growing up surrounded by technology, they become far more tech savvy than we might realise, and some young kids may even know how to use your phone better than you do.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">What if they decide they want to email Grandma, and inadvertently send that video of you singing along to Frozen to every single one of your colleagues? And we've all heard the horror stories about parents who leave their kids playing Angry Birds for 2 minutes, only to come back and discover they've somehow made £500 of in-app purchases! If you've recently entered your App Store password on an iPhone or an iPad, it's unlikely you'll be asked again that day, so if you happen to let your kids play on your device, you're practically giving them free reign over your account. On a Windows Phone, once an app is opened you're not even asked for a password before you are charged for the purchase. You don't want to have to continually hover over your child in order to watch exactly what they're doing when you let them play, so we've got some solutions for you. By child-proofing your device you can allow them to play in peace, safe in the knowledge that your bank account, and you privacy, are protected.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">As long as you're<strong> running iOS 6 or above</strong>, you will have a setting on your device called <strong>Guided Access</strong>. This tool is brilliant! Guided Access allows you to keep the current user in an app, which they can't exit without a passcode. You can also disable certain features in the app, preventing them from using anything you would prefer them not to have access to. To enable Guided Access ...</p>
1. Go to <strong>Settings</strong>

2. Click<strong> General</strong>, then <strong>Accessibility</strong>, then <strong>Guided Access</strong>

3. Turn on <strong>Guided Access</strong>

4. Set your <strong>passcode</strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Now, whenever your child wants to use your phone, simply load the app you want them to use and <strong>triple click the Home button</strong>. This is where you have the <strong>option to disable certain features</strong>. Let's use <a href="http://23snaps.com" target="_blank">23snaps</a> as an example; if your child wants to look at their timeline, but you don't want them to have the option to navigate around the app, or post new content, you can simply disable the navigation bar at the bottom by circling it. Once you click start they can still scroll through their feed, but they won't have the option to open any of the other features. If they try to exit the app, they will be unable to until you enter the password for them.</p>
<img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Guided-Access-1.png" alt="" width="200" /><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Guided-Access-2.png" alt="" width="200" />

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">If you're an <strong>Android</strong> user, your best option is to install an app that creates a "Kids Zone", where you can prevent your kids from accessing any apps that you have not decided are appropriate for them. We've given <strong>Kids Place</strong> a try, and would definitely recommend it. Once installed, you can add the apps of your choosing, and enable a passcode which will prevent the current user from leaving their Kids Place without your permission. If they try to return to the home screen without entering the passcode, they will be shown a warning and Kids Place will be relaunched.  You can <strong>set up multiple user profiles</strong>, so your children can each have their own dedicated account, and it's up to you if you want to let them switch between accounts without the passcode. The only downside that we've come across with this particular app, is that there seems to be <strong>no way to disable the in-app purchasing options</strong> - so choose the apps you include wisely. In spite of this small drawback, this makes allowing the kids to play games on your phone or tablet so much easier. Every time they ask to play, simply open your child-proofed Kid's Place, and leave them to it.</p>
<img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Kids-Place-1.png" alt="" width="160" /><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Kids-Place-2.png" alt="" width="160" /><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Kids-Place-3.png" alt="" width="160" /><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Kids-Place-4.png" alt="" width="160" />

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">Finally, for Windows Phone users, there is an in-built option similar to the Android app described above, called <strong>Kid's Corner</strong>. Again, this allows you to basically set up a<strong> separate user profile for your kids</strong> that allows you to decide what games, music, videos, and apps your child can access.</p>
To set up your Kid’s Corner ...

1. Go to <strong>Settings</strong>

2. Open <strong>Kid’s Corner</strong> and turn it <strong>ON</strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;">From there you can choose which apps you want to add to each category. You can <strong>access your Kid’s Corner straight from your lock screen</strong>. Instead of swiping up to unlock the phone, swipe left to right and that will reveal a separate lock screen that reads “Kid’s Corner”. Swipe up the same way that you would swipe to unlock your phone and that's it, you have your very own child-proofed, custom designed home screen right there in Kid’s Corner.</p>
<img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/kids-corner-1.png" alt="" width="200" /><img src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/kids-corner-2.png" alt="" width="200" />

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst enabling these tools will go a long way to helping keep your devices safe in small hands, the best and most important way to secure your phone or tablet is to <strong>educate your child</strong> on how to properly use them, and make sure they understand what is acceptable behaviour and what is not. But, as a parent, a little extra security always helps, right?</p>
&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Fall Family Photo Ideas</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/fall-family-photo-ideas/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 08 Oct 2014 11:30:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rachell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096744</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Looking for ideas on how to make the most out of your family photos this Fall? Look no further!

Fall is such a beautiful time of the year! No wonder we all grab our cameras and head out to snaps hundreds of photos of the pretty Autumn colors, with the family in tow. There are many reasons why Fall is a favorite among families: the amazing transformation of the nature in parks, lakes and fields; the leaves that change colors and turn into a rainbow of reds, amber, and golden tones; the sunsets become even more gorgeous, and of course, the lighting is perfect for photographers!

Whether you hire a professional photographer for your family photos or decide to take those picture on your own, here are five great ideas to inspire you to make your Fall family photos even more special:

1- Be creative with leaves, the most iconic symbol of this season! You can create basically anything with leaves, from your children's age to heart and smiles.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall-leaves-photo-23snaps.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096764" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall-leaves-photo-23snaps.jpg" alt="fall leaves photo 23snaps" width="500" /></a>

<i> Source: <a href="”http://www.writingchapterthree.com/2012/10/we-heart-ny.html”">Writing Chapter Three</a></i>, <a href="”http://www.pinterest.com/pin/486248090991030724/”">Pinterest</a>

2- Go for pumpkins! No matter whether you pick them up from a supermarket, or go to a pumpkin field, they are always a good way to add some instant seasonal spice to your photos. And don't forget to play with all the different sizes, colors and shapes of our beloved pumpkins.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall-pumpkin-photo-23snaps.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096765" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall-pumpkin-photo-23snaps.jpg" alt="fall pumpkin photo 23snaps" width="500" /></a>

<i> Source: <a href="”http://moms.popsugar.com/Fall-Family-Portrait-Ideas-35815377”">Popsugar Moms</a></i>, <a href="”http://josephmichael.ca/blognew/2010/11/family-portrait-gabe-and-the-pumpkin/”">Joseph Michael Photography</a>

3- Dogs are welcome, after all, they are also part of the family! This tip also applies to any pet your family might have. They can also be a great entertainment for the children during the photoshoot.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall_dog_photo.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096763" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/fall_dog_photo.jpg" alt="fall_dog_photo" width="500" /></a>

<i> Source: <a href="”http://www.familypictureideashq.net/fall-family-picture-ideas-perfect-pets/”">Family Picture Ideas HQ</a></i>

4- Bring vintage objects to the scene, they can provide a special and unique touch to your photos. Objects like wagons, bikes, chairs and wooden toys can do the trick!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/vintage-fall-photo-23snaps-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096784" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/vintage-fall-photo-23snaps-2.jpg" alt="vintage fall photo 23snaps 2" width="500" /></a>

<i> Source: <a href="”http://www.momentsbyadrianmurray.com/”">Adrian Murray Photography</a></i>, <a href="”http://www.pinterest.com/pin/408842472396493827//”">Pinterest</a>

5- Choose amazing backgrounds. Well, this one is pretty easy since Fall offers such a large range of options. When choosing your background, look for interesting textures, lighting and colors that will compose the photo. The colorful trees are a must, but it could also be a red brick or stone wall or the reflection of the sky in a lake.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/stunning-background-fall-photo-23snaps-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740096783" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/stunning-background-fall-photo-23snaps-2.jpg" alt="stunning background fall photo 23snaps 2" width="500" /></a>

<i> Source: <a href="”http://www.cuded.com/2013/03/50-examples-of-family-photography/”">Cuded</a>, <a href="”http://www.babble.com/babble-voices/tis-the-season-12-tips-for-taking-amazing-family-holiday-photos/”">Babble</a></i>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Global Handwashing Day - How to Avoid Common Colds &amp; Flu this Winter</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/global-handwashing-day-how-to-avoid-common-colds-flu-this-winter/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 15 Oct 2014 13:54:56 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096905</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">In honour of today's <em><strong><a href="http://globalhandwashing.org/ghw-day">Global Handwashing Day</a></strong></em>, we wanted to help you out with some tips to keep you and your family cold, flu, and generally germ free this winter. A lot of the causes of colds and flu can pass unacknowledged because they usually happen ten to twelve days before the actual symptoms appear, as this is the incubation period for many colds and coughs. With our tips, you can stay one step ahead of the game and have a much better chance of <strong>keeping <em>your family germ free</em></strong>.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Wash your hands</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">"<em><strong>Handwashing with soap is one of the cheapest most effective 'vaccines'</strong></em> against viral diseases from the seasonal flu to the common cold" says <a href="http://www.menafn.com/1093980940/Handwashing-one-important-tool-in-the-Ebola-fightUNICEFGlobal-Handwashing-Day-a-reminder-that-the-simple-practice-saves-lives">Sanjay Wijesekera</a>, Head of UNICEF's W.A.S.H. programmes.  Whilst it's true that a lot of infections are mainly carried in the air, and are transmitted when someone coughs or sneezes, germs can also be transmitted by physical contact and enter the body when infected hands touch vulnerable parts like our eyes, mouths and noses. Washing hands regularly - and drying them on disposable paper towels (or making sure hand towels are washed frequently) - can significantly reduce the chances of catching a virus.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Keep warm</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Wrapping yourself up against the cold is a great defence to keep from catching a chill. <em><strong>Shivering actually depresses the immune system</strong></em>, this is because our bodies' resources go towards keeping us warm, rather than fighting off any germs - increasing the likelihood of catching a cold.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Watch the weather</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Low cloud, dull and misty conditions tend to bring an increase in germ. <em><strong>Viruses can survive longer in moist conditions</strong></em>. They can hang in the air attached to water droplets more easily, and when it's cloudy and dull there are fewer breezes to blow the germs away.</p>
<em> </em>
<h3>Clean Regularly</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It is just as easy for viruses to pass from a surface to person, as from person to person. Things like phones, pens, doorknobs, and remote controls can easily harbour the germs of all the people who have previously touched them. Making a point to clean regularly can reduce the number of germs, and therefore - the chance of infection. Carrying a small packet of antiseptic wipes to <em><strong>wipe down commonly-used surfaces</strong></em> can be useful.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Don't Use Your Hand To Cover Your Mouth</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">When you cough or sneeze, cover your mouth and nose with a tissue, then put your used tissue in the bin. If you don't have a tissue, <em><strong>cough or sneeze into your upper sleeve or elbow</strong></em>, not your hands. Coughing into your hand will increase the chance of spreading the germs through physical contact.</p>
<em> </em>
<h3>Eat a Balanced Diet</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Ensuring your diet contains a variety of vitamins and mineral can help keep the germs at bay. There is also some strong arguments for the value of Zinc as an essential mineral to to help fight colds and provide a boost to a flagging immune system. Good food sources include meat, oysters, eggs, seafood, tofu, black- eyed peas and wheat germ. It might be tough to convince the kids to chow down on some of these options, so you can also purchase child-friendly vitamin supplements to help them out. <em><strong>Zinc and Vitamin C make a great cold-busting duo</strong></em>.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Drink plenty</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Doctors recommend we drink about eight glasses of water a day to stay healthy, but this also includes the water included in the food you eat - like fruits and vegetables. Before catching a cold, being dehydrated makes your mucus drier and thicker and <em><strong>less able to cope against invading bacteria and viruses</strong></em>. If you've already caught a cold, drinking plenty of fluids will help flush out the infection.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Sleep soundly</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Few things help to keep your immune system in great shape as a good night's sleep. <em><strong>It is whilst you sleep that your body recharges</strong></em>, and works to restore any possible damage done during the day. Not giving your body adequate time to return to it's optimum can increase the chance of invading germs of taking hold.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>Keep on moving</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Exercise boosts your immune system, and can help prevent cold and flu viruses from making you sick. When you exercise; the number of <em><strong>natural killer (NK) cells in your body increase</strong></em>, and it is these cells that seek out and destroy the invading bacteria and viruses. Additionally, warding off extra weight is important for overall health, particularly when it comes to preventing colds and flu.</p>
&nbsp;
<h3>The Bottom Line</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst all of the tips above can help to keep germs at bay, and ward off infections, the most effective way to stay free of flu this winter is to <em><strong>get yourself and your children a flu shot</strong></em>. Here in the UK it is also possible to get a flu vaccine in the form of a <a href="http://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vaccinations/pages/child-flu-vaccine.aspx">nasal spray</a> for children - as it's quick and completely painless, there will be no need for your kids to endure the dreaded needle.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Tips To Ensure Your Kids Stay Safe Online</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/tips-to-ensure-your-kids-stay-safe-online/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 25 Oct 2014 13:55:04 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rachell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096776</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst your children are growing up, as a parent, you are responsible for their well-being. Whilst this obviously refers to their physical presence, their digital presence should also be of your concern. As more and more of our daily interactions happen digitally, <em><strong>making sure your kids are safe online is imperative</strong></em>.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The fact is, we are all spending a lot of time on the internet these days and we know that it can offer not only entertainment, but also numerous learning opportunities, and potential stumbling-blocks, for our children. Computer skills are also increasingly vital in today's society. With that said, <strong>completely prohibiting your children from going online isn't practical</strong>, even if it is out of concern for their safety. By combining real-life care methods with security software and technology, you can easily decrease some of the more prominent pitfalls.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Whether your kids are using the Internet for study, just for gaming or accessing social networks, by following these tips you can help to educate your children on acceptable practise online, whilst also improving their online security knowledge and keeping an eye on what they're up to:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">1. Keep yourself up to date with current digital trends. Learn about all the new technologies, social networks and tools that your children use, to ensure your aware of the any difficulties they may come up against.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">2. If you wish, you can install parental monitoring and controlled-access software on your computer. With these programmes, you can limit what your child can or cannot access, and keep an eye of their activities.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">3. Set up the computer in a communal area of the house. This way, you and other family members can keep an eye on what the kids are up to. Although we do understand that the concept of a "family computer" may be somewhat outdated, perhaps you could implement a "tech zone" in a communal space where all tablets and smartphones live - and from which they cannot be removed.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">4. Be conscious of, and informed about, all the available social networking sites. If your children want to start using any social network, be sure are old enough to meet the minimum age requirements for signing up. Most networks require a minimum age of 13 to create an account in accordance with <a href="http://www.coppa.org/">COPPA</a> guideline. Then, sit with them throughout the sign up and make sure they enable the correct privacy settings for their account, so they can restrict who has access to their profiles and photos.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">5. Discuss with your child what you consider appropriate behaviour online. Talk about good practice and acceptable behaviour, such as never posting content publicly, not revealing personal information, avoiding posting personal photos, not giving out their passwords and never accepting any invitation from a stranger. It's also a good idea to insist that they are 'friends' with you on the various social networks they choose to use.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">6. Keep a list of all of the passwords set to your child's online accounts. Advise them that if they wish to build a digital presence, you will be monitoring it. Let them know that if you suspect they are not following your guidelines, that you may choose to check their account. This shouldn't be a threat, but a mutual understanding that they need to use good judgement, and if they don't, there will be consequences.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">7. Periodically check the chat and search history, and the sites that your child has accessed. Every week, 'google' the name of your child and see whether they are posting anything publicly. If you find any public content, or anything you are unhappy with, call your child for a chat and speak clearly about why that content shouldn't be there.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">8. Report sites and users performing illegal activities, and encourage your child to do the same. If you think a site has collected inappropriate information from your kids or marketed to them in a way that violates the law, report it to the appropriate legal authorities. In the United States, for example, this can be done through the <a href="http://ftc.gov/complaint">FTC</a>.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">9. Explain to your child that they should only ever open emails or messages from people they know in real-life. Advise them that emails from strangers can contain viruses and spam that would damage the computer and leak confidential information to malicious recipients.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">10. And finally, one of the most important pieces of advice to give to your child is that they can find same problems online that experience in the real-world. Encourage them to tell you if they feel threatened by someone or uncomfortable because of something online. Advise them that what they share in their network can reach a huge number of people - far beyond their comprehension - and that there is no getting it back, so being aware of the consequences of everything they do online is extremely important. They need to be aware that even when they use the internet outside of their home and school, or other devices, the should know how to act and respect the same rules followed at home.</p>
<em>Image Source: <a href="http://carunews.blogspot.co.uk/2012/12/according-to-survey-on-parents-they.html" target="_blank">Caru News</a>, <a href="http://www.idt911.com/KnowledgeCenter/NewsAlerts/NewsAlertDetail.aspx?a=%7BD17A4F62-3E8F-4EBF-AC3B-749911CA7DC8%7D" target="_blank">IDT911</a></em>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

		<wp:post_date_gmt>2014-10-25 13:55:04</wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status>closed</wp:comment_status>

	<item>
				<title>All Of Your Family Can Now Help You Build Your Online Photo Journal</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/all-of-your-family-can-now-help-you-build-your-online-photo-journal/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 19 Oct 2014 16:00:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096817</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">We're super excited to announce the release of our newest feature ... the ability for all of the people in your family network to help contribute to your child's timeline in your 23snaps journal! With the release of our latest update, 23snaps has become even more of an interactive online photobook - making it even more enjoyable for the whole family.</p>
If your kids spend the weekend with Grandma &amp; Grandpa, the Grandparents can share those photos from their own 23snaps profiles and still add them directly to your children's timelines, simple by tagging them. Obviously, protecting your right as a parent to decide what photos you want to see on your child's feed is important, which is why you get final say before a tag of your child is applied. Whenever anyone in your network wants to tag one of your little ones, you will receive a notification that gives you the opportunity to accept or decline the tag.

This feature has been requested by so many of our users, and we're really pleased to have finally made it a reality! Read on to find out exactly how the whole system works, or go and check it out for yourself! You can use our new family tagging options on the 23snaps <a href="http://23snaps.com/me">website</a>, or you can download our latest update for <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/23snaps-family-album-private/id526481189?mt=8">iOS</a> or <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.snaps23.android&amp;hl=en_GB">Android</a> to try it out.
<p style="text-align: left;"><em>               <a href="#TPT_how">How It Works</a> <em>                          </em></em><em><a href="#TPT_single">New Posts</a>                             <em><a href="#TPT_existing">Existing Posts</a> </em>                   <em><a href="#TPT_accept">Accepting a Tag</a>  </em></em></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">           <a href="#TPT_how"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096844" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/TPT-Thumbnail-Family-150x150.png" alt="TPT Thumbnail Family" width="100" height="100" /></a>                  <a href="#TPT_single"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096845" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/TPT-Thumbnail-Post-150x150.png" alt="TPT Thumbnail Post" width="100" height="100" /></a>                   <a href="#TPT_existing"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096846" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/TPT-Thumbnail-Tag-150x150.png" alt="TPT Thumbnail Tag" width="100" height="100" /></a>               <a href="#TPT_accept"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-39740096843" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/TPT-Thumbnail-Accept-150x150.png" alt="TPT Thumbnail Accept" width="100" height="100" /></a></p>
&nbsp;

<a name="TPT_how"></a>

&nbsp;
<h3 class="entry-title">How it works</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Your family &amp; friends can now help you to build your children's timelines on 23snaps. By tagging your children in their posts, their content will be added to your child's timeline, pending your authorisation. Your connections can tag your child in any post except measurement updates; including photos, videos, Stories and status updates. Please be aware that this will make that post visible to all of the people you are connected to, <strong>even if those people are not directly connected to your connection</strong>. Those people will have the ability to like and comment on your connection's post, which will be visible to the person who originally tagged your child.</p>
&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<a name="TPT_single"></a>

&nbsp;
<h3 class="entry-title">Tagging Your Friends' Children in a New Post</h3>
<strong><em>On the iOS app</em></strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Click on the orange <strong>+</strong> button in the menu bar at the bottom of the screen, and then tap<em> </em>the icon for your preferred post type. Once you have selected your photos or video, written your status or created your Story you will have the opportunity to tag your connections' child(ren) from the publishing screen. Simply tap the <em>Tag your connections' children </em>button, and select the child(ren) you wish to tag, then click <em>Done</em>. You can tag children from multiple families in one post. You also have the option to tag your own children and decide when on the timeline it should appear. Finally, tap the orange <em>Publish</em> button in the top right hand corner and your photo will be uploaded to 23snaps.</p>
Please be aware, your tag will require authorisation from the child's parents. If they choose to decline your tag, the post will remain on your timeline, but not on that of the child you tried to tag.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-1.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096818" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-1-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging iOS 1" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-2.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096819" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-2-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging iOS 2" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-3.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096820" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-3-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging iOS 2" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-4.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096821" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-4-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging iOS 2" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-5.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096822" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-5-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging iOS 2" width="128" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong><em>On the Android app</em></strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Click on the orange <strong>+</strong> button in the top right of the screen, and then tap<em> </em>the icon for your preferred post type. Once you have selected your photos or video, written your status or created your Story you will have the opportunity to tag your connections' child(ren) from the publishing screen. Simply tap the <em>Tag your connections' children </em>button, and select the child(ren) you wish to tag, then click <em>Done</em>. You can tag children from multiple families in one post. You also have the option to tag your own children and decide when on the timeline it should appear. Finally, tap the orange <em>Publish</em> button in the top right hand corner and your photo will be uploaded to 23snaps.</p>
Please be aware, your tag will require authorisation from the child's parents. If they choose to decline your tag, the post will remain on your timeline, but not on that of the child you tried to tag.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-11.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096828" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-11-189x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging  5" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-21.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096829" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-21-189x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging  5" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-31.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096830" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-31-189x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging  5" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-41.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096831" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-41-189x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging  5" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-51.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096832" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Post-51-189x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tagging  5" width="128" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<a name="TPT_existing"></a>

&nbsp;
<h3 class="entry-title">Tagging Your Friends' Children in an Existing Post</h3>
<strong><em>On the app</em></strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;">In the Newsfeed, or your Family Page, locate the photo you wish to tag. Tap the <em>Options</em> button and select <em>Edit Activity</em>. Now, simply tap the <em>Tag your friends' children </em>button, and select the child(ren) you wish to tag, then click <em>Done</em>. Finally, tap <em>Finish</em> to save your changes.</p>
Please be aware, your tag will require authorisation from the child's parents. If they choose to decline your tag, the post will remain on your timeline, but not on that of the child you tried to tag.

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-1.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096823" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-1-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tag 1" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-2.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096824" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-2-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tag 2" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-3.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096825" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-3-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tag 3" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-4.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096826" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-4-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tag 4" width="128" /></a> <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-5.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096827" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Retroactive-Tag-5-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Family Tag 5" width="128" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<a name="TPT_accept"></a>

&nbsp;
<h3 class="entry-title">Accepting a tag request for your child</h3>
<em><strong>On the app</strong></em>
<p style="text-align: justify;">When one of your connections tries to tag your child in their post, you will receive a notification of a pending tag. To accept the tag, locate the notification in your feed and tap to open it. You can preview the post by clicking on the grey arrow on the right of the thumbnail. To Accept the tag click on the orange <em>Accept </em>button.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-11.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096837" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-11-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Pending Family Tag 1" width="169" height="300" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-Accept-11.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096838" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-Accept-11-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Pending Family Tag 2" width="169" height="300" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-Accept-21.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096839" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Pending-Tag-Accept-21-169x300.png" alt="23snaps Pending Family Tag 3" width="169" height="300" /></a>

&nbsp;

	<item>
				<title>What I&#039;m Thankful For - Free Printable Thanksgiving Activity Pages</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/what-im-thankful-for-free-printable-thanksgiving-activity-pages/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 25 Nov 2014 11:30:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096971</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Keeping the kids entertained on Thanksgiving whilst your trying to get table set and the turkey prepared can be difficult, but we want to make it easy as possible for you. We've created these free printable activity pages to keep them occupied - they can colour in the title and the picture, and then write down 5 things they're thankful for. Having them share what they're thankful for around the dinner table will also be a lovely way to kick off the meal!

<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Turkey.pdf" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096969" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Turkey-212x300.jpg" alt="What I'm Thankful For - Turkey" width="212" height="300" /></a>   <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Pilgrims.pdf" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096967" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Pilgrims-212x300.jpg" alt="What I'm Thankful For - Pilgrims" width="212" height="300" /></a>   <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Horn-of-Plenty.pdf" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-39740096965" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Horn-of-Plenty-212x300.jpg" alt="What I'm Thankful For - Horn of Plenty" width="212" height="300" /></a>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Turkey.pdf" target="_blank">Download</a>                                        <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Pilgrims.pdf" target="_blank">Download</a>                                        <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/What-Im-Thankful-For-Horn-of-Plenty.pdf" target="_blank">Download</a></strong></p>

	<item>
				<title>The Perfect Christmas Gift For Families</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/the-perfect-christmas-gift-for-families/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 19 Nov 2014 13:00:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740096995</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Looking for the perfect Christmas gift for one of your favorite family members? Then look no further! The 23snaps enabled Wi-Fi Digital Photo Frame is the perfect present to show that special person how much they mean to you.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It has always been our mission, here are 23snaps, to make all of your cherished family photos accessible to everyone in your family, even if they're not very tech-savvy. Our digital photo frames can sit on a mantel piece or kitchen table, showcasing the latest family photos without any additional effort, making it an incredibly simple yet stylish way to share and enjoy photos of the children you love.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">What better gift is there than to give your loved ones an ever updating peek into your cherished family journal?</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The frames cost just $189 (£149) and are available in the UK &amp; Ireland, USA, Canada, Japan, France and Germany.</p>
<a href="http://shop.23snaps.com/products/23snaps-photo-frame" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-39740096993" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Buy-Now-Button-300x93.png" alt="Buy Now Button" width="200" height="63" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong><em>A little more info about what our digital frames can do:</em></strong>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>The Pix-Star Wi-Fi Digital Photo Frame, enabled for 23snaps, is the easiest way to share your family photos with your loved ones.</em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>The 10.4” digital frames are Wi-Fi enabled and arrive ready to connect to any existing 23snaps account when a user provides their credentials online. With your Pix-Star Frame, you can easily:</em></p>

<ul>
	<li><em>View photos from your 23snaps news feed, directly on your frame.</em></li>
	<li><em>Upload photos from your personal collection or computer to the frame, which includes 2GB of internal memory.</em></li>
	<li><em>Link other web albums such as Facebook, Flickr, Google+, and more.</em></li>
	<li><em>Remotely control albums from the Pix-Star web site and choose which albums to display on your frame.</em></li>
	<li><em>View photos as a collage or as an individual image on the frame.</em></li>
	<li><em>Enjoy all of your latest photos with automatic scrolling between photos stored on the frame.</em></li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>There is no monthly fee, and you benefit from the fantastic customer support of the 23snaps and Pix-Star teams to help you get the most out of your new frame. </em></p>]]></content:encoded>

				<title>How Parents Experience The Holidays</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/how-parents-experience-the-holidays/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 03 Dec 2014 16:30:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097008</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h4 style="text-align: left;">When you've finished your shopping &amp; the kids start
asking for a whole load of new things.</h4>

	<item>
				<title>Do you keep a baby book?</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/do-you-keep-a-baby-book/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Nov 2014 14:30:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097021</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Do you keep a baby book? Some parents feel pressured to do so meticulously, begrudging the time it takes them, whilst others can't find the time at all ... and then wish they had.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst rigorous, baby-related record keeping isn't for everyone, keeping a log of all of the most important moments in your child's life can be simple - and enjoyable. You could choose to go more traditional; with a physical book into which you can stick the lock of hair from their first hair cut, a clipping from the newspaper on the day they were born, written notes about first smiles, words &amp; steps, and all of the other lovely little mementos you acquire along the way. Or you could keep a baby box, which is basically a simplified version of the baby book, only with no fear of anything falling out of it!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">But with the digital universe constantly evolving, it is now resplendent with easy storage options for this very thing. We spoke to one UK based mum, who used the memo function on her phone to keep track of all the important firsts. She then paired that text with the photos also stored on her phone - which she had printed in a beautiful photo book in time for her daughter's first birthday.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://23snaps.com" target="_blank">23snaps</a> is another option to make keeping a record for your child even easier. You can quickly and easily add the little moments as they happen, right from your phone or tablet. If you're not great at thinking about making a note of those moments in real time, you can even add the photos and videos that you take days or weeks later, and they will still be added to the right moment on your child's timeline, based on the time and date information in the media file. You can also share your child's digital baby book in a private network with your family &amp; close friends.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Trying to record all of the special moments might feel like a chore, as a parent - you want to be involved in the memorable moments with your children, not watching from the sidelines trying to commit everything to memory. But taking photos and videos is something we do almost every day, whether consciously trying to keep a record, or just because the kids are doing something adorable. Consolidating all of those moments in a dedicated environment makes it so much easier to look back and remember them later, and that way, your child can look back on them with you. There is no real way to pass a memory from your mind to theirs, but with a physical record - be it traditional or digital - you have something to that was produced with love, to pass down to your children as they grow up.</p>
&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/happy-halloween-from-23snaps/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 31 Oct 2014 10:30:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097045</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Sharing Baby Photos Online - 3 Mums&#039; Opinions</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/sharing-baby-photos-online-3-mums-opinions/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 11 Nov 2014 12:30:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097048</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">There are many arguments for and against sharing photos of your children online. Whilst it's a great way to keep an <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/online-family-album-inheriting-a-family-legacy/">archive of all your wonderful photos</a>, there are lots of things to consider; like privacy, oversharing and digital safety.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Here at <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=share_online&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps">23snaps</a>, we think that sharing is great, but we prefer to do so in an environment that we know is private. With the digital world advancing in leaps and bounds, there are now loads of great ways to share your photos online, but for some parents the idea of uploading their precious photos to the internet makes them feel uncomfortable. We spoke to three mums who all feel very differently about sharing their kids' photos online, and we wanted to find out what their reasons were ...</p>
&nbsp;
<h3><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Up.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-39740097061 size-thumbnail" style="padding-bottom: 5px;" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Up-150x150.png" alt="Thumbs Up" width="150" height="150" /></a>Leanne, Sussex - Pro Sharing (Public)</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>"I'm very open when it comes to sharing the photos of my daughter online. There are entire albums dedicated to her on Facebook, and my Instagram feed is full of her pictures. I have a big family, who are spread all over the world, so when my daughter was born it never occurred to me to share her photos in any other way than on social media, where I already kept up to date with my family. </em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>I'm not really concerned about keeping her photos private, because all of the photos I put online are photos that I would genuinely be happy for anyone to see. There are the odd bathing suit pictures, but I don't ever share photos of her with no clothes on, which is the only thing I would be concerned about getting into the wrong hands. I share photos of myself on social media, and nothing bad has ever come of it. I also know that I am able to protect my daughter in real life - so I really don't see the harm.</em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>Now that she's old enough to have a basic understanding of what Facebook is, she loves that her grandparents, aunts and uncles can all see the photos of her (she LOVES having her photo taken), and always likes to see if anyone comments on her photo. When she is old enough to have her own social media accounts, she will be able to connect with me and see all of her baby photos, whenever she wants."</em></p>
&nbsp;
<h3><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Up-Yellow.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-39740097066 size-thumbnail" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Up-Yellow-150x150.png" alt="Thumbs Up Yellow" width="150" height="150" /></a>Steph, London - Pro Sharing (Private)</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>"When I had my little boy, I knew I wanted to be able to share the photos that I took of him, but I really didn't like the idea of doing so publicly. There are all those horrible stories of what happens to kids photos online, and I didn't want that to happen to my family. I also wanted the option to be quite discerning about who I let see the pictures. </em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>On Facebook I'm 'friends' with about 800 people, of those people I am actually real-life friends with about 50 of them. There are people I haven't seen since school, or have met once and then never seen again. I didn't like the idea of these people having access to all my baby photos, but also; I didn't want to become one of those mums that spams everyone's newsfeeds pictures that they have no interest in seeing. I wanted to be able to share my photos without having to be concerned about the reaction they might get, or who might see them. So I opted for a private network. I tried a few different things before I settled on 23snaps, which is perfect for me. I also back everything up to Dropbox, and most of my backed up files are also shared with my family, so they can access the photos there too if they want. But 23snaps is where most of my family look at the photos, and interact with me, my husband and our little boy. Knowing that my photos are secure, and not having to censor myself, makes me really happy. </em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>It's also a great way to keep a timeline for my son, like an online baby book, so he will be able to look back through all of the photos when he gets a bit older. I think it will also help him avoid the inevitable embarrassment that the kids whose parents share everything on Facebook will feel when they get to their teenage years, and all of their friends will have easy access to their potty training pictures!"</em></p>
<em> </em>
<h3><a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Down.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-39740097060 size-thumbnail" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Thumbs-Down-150x150.png" alt="Thumbs Down" width="150" height="150" /></a>Emily, Surrey - Anti Sharing</h3>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>"There is not a single photo of either of my children online, anywhere ... and that's exactly the way I like it. But then, there are very few photos of me either.When I was growing up my parents took photos of me and my siblings, put them in an album or put them in the post to our relatives, and no one felt deprived. I don't see why that has to change. </em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>I guess I'm pretty traditional, I love looking back through my babybook - the pages have aged and the book is delicate, but it gives me the feeling that I'm holding a significant part of my own history in my hands. It just wouldn't feel the same if I had to sit at a computer to see those photos. </em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>I'm also a bit paranoid about who might be able to get their hands on my photos if I put them online. We're constantly bombarded with news about celebrity photos being leaked, or hackers accessing private information online, and I feel that as hard as you might work to keep your details private, putting them online makes them accessible to people in a way that keeping them off the internet altogether just doesn't. I'm not completely anti-technology though, I do send my friends and family photos via email or text - I just want to have the option to decide who sees what, and when.</em></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>At the end of the day, my world revolves around keeping my children safe from harm, so why would I invite the possibility of something bad happening by putting information about them out there on the web? It just doesn't make sense to me."</em></p>
&nbsp;

It seems there's no right or wrong answer when it comes to sharing your kids photos online - it's all about what feels right for your family. But if you're interested to find out a little bit more about sharing your photos privately on <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=share_online&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps">23snaps</a> - why not <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=share_onlie&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=website">check out our website</a>?]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Grandparents VS Technology</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/grandparents-vs-technology/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 29 Oct 2014 17:49:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rachell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097055</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Have you noticed how the way grandparents interact with technology has changed in the last few years? More and more grandmas and grandpas have begun to realise that using a smartphone or tablet is essential if they want to be able to keep up with, and feel close to, their younger family members. It seems that the weekly calls and annual postcards are no longer enough for those who always want to be in the loop when it comes to the lives of their grandchildren.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">For the younger generation, who grew up with technology, sending and receiving photos and videos through a computer or mobile device seems like nothing special. But for grandparents, aunts, &amp; uncles from older generations, this process can still be quite challenging. If we take a real look around, it's becoming clear to see that a lot of grandparents are trying hard to be part of the new era. Many are taking computer classes, whilst others are opting to upgrade their old phones to smartphones or tablets, in the hopes that their family will teach them how to use their new gadgets. There are numerous organisations and websites dedicated to providing the relevant information for the less tech-savvy generation, and help bring this group together through forums and online communities. Here are some of the great sites we've found:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://www.gransnet.com/" target="_blank">Gransnet</a> -  An online portal where visitors can join forums to help them connect with other people online. There are also loads of great articles and information about local events happening in the area. Gransnet also has their own social network that helps grandparents get used to being online, stay connected and exchange experiences.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://www.grandparents.com/" target="_blank">Grandparents.com</a> - Managed by AGA, the American Grandparents Association, this website offers everything for grandparents - it’s a great tool to help them get used to browsing the web. There’s expert information on a huge variety of topic, from games to recipes, advice on family and relationships, as well as health and wellbeing. By signing up to their Premium membership, users can also receive discounts from the AGA’s partner services.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://www.proudgrandparents.co.uk/aboutoursite.html" target="_blank">ProudGrandparents</a> - This is another website that is focused on having experts create the highest quality information possible. The site offers a lot of tips and advice on technology, balancing work and family, as well as articles that help grandparents stay informed about their legal and financial rights.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The Grannies and Grandads who do overcome the challenges and manage to adapt to the changes of this new technological era can be considered very lucky to be able to keep up to date with their little ones' special moments, that are now shared exclusively online. But what about those who haven't mastered the necessary technology, and are still missing out? In order to find out a bit more about the way that grandparents are handling tech, <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=grandparents_tech&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps" target="_blank">23snaps</a> organised a survey (conducted by OnePoll) that showed interesting - yet not altogether unexpected - results.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">A sample of 500 grandparents aged 40+ were interviewed. It was found that almost two thirds (64%) don’t, or are unable to, use the social networks and websites where family photos are shared. Among those who do have access to social networks, less than 1 in 10 (9.8%) feel comfortable on sites like Flickr and Instagram. And even though half (53%) of those grandparents are on Facebook, only one in three (36%) say they are connected in all of the places that family photos are shared.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">These results show that although it might seem easy for the older generation to sign up for the popular networks and photo sharing services that are available today, it doesn't mean that they will find them easy to navigate, causing them not to stick around long-term. The truth is that these platforms were not designed with the less technologically savvy users in mind. Most networks are not particularly intuitive for those who don't already understand how they work, and few offer a private, secure environment where the uninitiated would feel comfortable getting their bearings. With the constant introduction of new features, tools and information - it can make it even more difficult for grandparents to find the content that really matters to them - the photos and updates about their grandchildren.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It has always been <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=grandparents_tech&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps" target="_blank">23snaps</a>’ priority to be accessible to even the least tech-savvy family members, and the generation who misses out on cherished family moments that are now shared primarily online. With a simple user interface, the option to subscribe to email-only updates and making sure that the photos that matter are always easy to find, <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=grandparents_tech&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps" target="_blank">23snaps</a> helps to bring the whole family together.</p>
&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<i> Images Source: <a href="http://boomergrandparents.com/tech-tips-via-youtube-tutorials/seniors-using-computer/" target="”_blank”">Boomer Grandparents</a></i>, <a href="http://familiesintheloop.com/new-and-noteworthy/12920/grandparents-and-technology-how-to-use-it/" target="”_blank”">Families in the Loop</a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Shop Savvy &amp; Save Money This Christmas</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/shop-savvy-this-christmas/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 15 Nov 2014 17:00:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097082</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst Christmas may be the most wonderful time of the year, it is also a time of extravagance and over-spending!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Trying to keep hold of your pennies over the holidays can seem like an impossible task - especially if you get caught up in the excitement of gift giving. BUT ... there are a few ways to shop savvy and help curb your spending without having to feel like a Scrooge - and our resident penny pincher will tell you how!</p>
&nbsp;
<h5>Shop online</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">As Christmas approaches, the high street becomes a veritable Santa's Grotto - with festive music on repeat, twinkly lights on every surface, and the smell of roasting chestnuts wafting through the air. It's so difficult to restrain yourself when you get swept up in the excitement of Christmas shopping - especially when all those gifts you'd never even thought of are right there on display. By staying off the high street and out of the shopping malls, it's much easier to avoid the temptation to over spend.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Write yourself a list of the items you need to buy and search for them one by one, as this will prevent you from stumbling across the little "extras" by chance - as those add up!  Google will also compare the prices from various online stores to help you make sure you're getting the best deal.</p>
&nbsp;
<h5>Earn cashback</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Did you know that you can now get paid to shop?! Sites like <a href="http://www.quidco.com/">Quidco</a> allow you to earn cashback whenever you shop from one of the companies or brands they partner with ... and there are hundreds to choose from. The amount of cashback varies from brand to brand, but you can generally earn between about 3-8% cashback on your purchase - and sometimes you'll even get extra perks thrown in - like free shipping.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Quidco is free to join, and super easy to use. Simply sign in to your account and search for the company or brand you want to shop - then click through from Quidco so that they can track your purchase, and you will have the cashback paid into your account within a couple of weeks. If you shop savvy year round, you can earn hundreds of pounds in cashback, which would basically pay for Christmas.</p>
&nbsp;
<h5>Check eBay</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Bag yourself a bargain by checking for your desired products on <a href="http://www.ebay.co.uk/">eBay</a> before buying them in store or online elsewhere. Whilst a lot of the items sold on eBay are second hand, and you might not fancy giving a pre-owned gift, there are hundred of new products on there sold by stores that operate solely on eBay. They want to compete with the better known stores, and so strive to beat the RRP. If you can't find a cheaper option, at least you'll know you're getting a good deal buying from your usual retailer.</p>
&nbsp;
<h5>Buy early or late</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Did you know that most stores work on a pretty common sale strategy? If you shop early, you can get a great deal - and the same goes if you leave your shopping to the last minute. After Halloween, until mid-November, a lot of stores offer great deals on a number of items, to encourage you to do your Christmas shopping with them before you go elsewhere.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">However, come the middle of December most of those items will go back up to full price, until around the 20th of December. It's during this time that the majority of people purchase their gifts, and the stores don't want to miss out on the opportunity to earn maximum revenue; so it's best to avoid doing your shopping then if you can.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Then - right before Christmas - prices tend to drop again. This is what used to be called the January Sales, then the Boxing Day Sales and now seem to be the Christmas Eve (Eve Eve Eve Eve) sales. All retailers want to be the first to launch their sales, in order to get the really keen sale shoppers through their doors before they run out of funds, so you can often take advantage of the early-bird sales to get some last minute present shopping done, on a budget.</p>
&nbsp;
<h5>Don't get caught out by BOGOF or 3 for 2 offers</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Multiple purchase offers can save you loads of cash - if you actually need all of the items in the offer. More often than not, though, you end up buying the extra items because it seems like a good deal. A good example of this is with Buy One Get One Free offers; I often find that the item I actually want is the cheaper option in the offer - so effectively I get it for free if I purchase another item at a higher price. This then means that someone ends up with a gift that they probably don't want, or I get stuck with a useless item, all because I wanted the original item for free. And the amount I actually ended up paying for the gift I wanted and the item I didn't, was more than if I'd just bought the original gift on it's own.</p>
Think about it sensibly, unless you actually need all of the items on offer - don't get sucked in!

&nbsp;
<h5>Use Voucher Codes</h5>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It's possible to find an offer for practically any item you want these days. I will NEVER buy something online without first doing a quick search for "voucher code for <em>X shop</em>".</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">You can also sign up for companies like Voucher Codes, who will send you regular emails with all of the valid codes they have that day. <a href="http://www.vouchercodes.co.uk/">VoucherCodes.co.uk</a> negotiate exclusive offers with their partners, that generally can't be found elsewhere. They also make it their priority to ensure they only ever send you codes that are still valid - as there's nothing more annoying than getting to the checkout, thinking you've bagged yourself a bargain, only to find out the code has expired!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It's fair to say that a lot of these codes won't necessarily be of great use to you, but you will regularly receive a gem that will save you a TON of money.  You can also edit your preferences depending on the type of product you're interested in.</p>
&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">Whilst Christmas isn't necessarily the easiest time to keep to a budget, it can be done - and without too much work or stress. Shop savvy and you'll enjoy all the best bits of Christmas, without having to fear checking your bank balance.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Finally, one last tip to save you money on a great gift for your family ... order your <a href="https://23snaps.com?utm_source=shop_savvy&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=23snaps">23snaps</a> photobook before the 25th November (or the 10th of December if you're in the UK) and <a href="https://23snaps.com/order/create?utm_source=shop_savvy&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=30_off">get 30% of the total cost</a>! Just enter the code FESTIVESNAPS at the checkout to redeem your discount.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">If you have any other tips for saving money when shopping for the holidays please let us know - because every little helps!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Data Security - Protect Your Privacy</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/data-security-protect-your-privacy/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 23 Nov 2014 14:00:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lucy]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097084</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">Data privacy is becoming more and more of an issue for people today, and we should all be taking extra precautions to make sure our data is kept secure. Xiaomi, a Chinese smartphone company, <a href="http://www.v3.co.uk/v3-uk/news/2359714/chinese-android-smartphone-firm-xiaomi-caught-collecting-users-data">recently made the news</a> because they were found to be transmitting data from all over the world - back to their servers. This included IMEI and phone number from the device, as well as the phone number of any contacts added to the phone book and from received SMS messages. Being aware of exactly what data is being sent from your device, and to where, is so important.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Our first piece of advice? <em>Don't keep sensitive data on your smartphone or tablet!</em> Taking and sharing photos, storing documents and communicating via SMS, MMS, and email are all generally okay - but any private information, such as banking details, social security (US) or national insurance (UK) numbers, and health records, should be kept elsewhere. This is even more important if you have no encryption or password protection in place.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">But, how can you know if your smartphone is betraying you and sending out your data? Most smartphones will prompt you to install a number of third-party apps that could potentially threaten your data privacy. This means you need to be aware of where your data is going.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">In order to be an careful as possible, we'd recommend you only download apps from dedicated app stores - as this means they will predominantly have been approved by Google, Apple or Microsoft. However, there are some apps that may still slip through the net and pose a risk to your data - so it's better to be safe than sorry, right?</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">That's why we'd also recommend that you install some software that will allow you to keep track of exactly what data is being transmitted, so that you can remove the offending app from your device. <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.eolwral.osmonitor&amp;hl=en">OSMonitor</a> is a great app, which is currently available for Android only, that provides details about which app is connecting to which server - as well as giving you the IP address of the server.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-1.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097089" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-1-170x300.png" alt="OS Monitor 1" width="126" height="221" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-2.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097090" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-2-169x300.png" alt="OS Monitor 2" width="125" height="221" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-3.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097091" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-3-168x300.png" alt="OS Monitor 3" width="124" height="221" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-4.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097092" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-4-169x300.png" alt="OS Monitor 4" width="125" height="221" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-5.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097093" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/OS-Monitor-5-169x300.png" alt="OS Monitor 5" width="125" height="221" /></a>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Another, slightly more comprehensive, option that is available for iOS as well as Android is <a href="https://viaforensics.com/products/viaprotect/">viaProtect</a>. This free app will scan the data that is being sent from your device without your knowledge. It will then reveal exactly what is happening in the background, making you aware of which apps are running and what they are doing. viaProtect will also monitor your device and network for any security vulnerabilities, and notify you whenever it detects anything new that might compromise your data. Once the app is installed, you are easily able to see whether your phone or tablet is risk-free, or if not - the percentage of risk it is currently in, you are also informed of what the risks are.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-1.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097094" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-1-168x300.png" alt="viaProtect 1" width="154" height="274" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-21.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097102" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-21-170x300.png" alt="" width="156" height="274" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-3.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097096" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-3-169x300.png" alt="viaProtect 3" width="155" height="274" /></a>  <a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-4.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-39740097097" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/viaProtect-4-171x300.png" alt="viaProtect 4" width="156" height="274" /></a>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It's always better to be safe than sorry, so make sure you're taking care to protect yourself and your data.</p>
Image Source: <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.eolwral.osmonitor&amp;hl=en">Google Play</a>, <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/viaprotect-free-mobile-security/id745063922?mt=8">App Store</a>,]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Happy Thanksgiving - 5 facts about turkey that you didn&#039;t know until now!</title>
		<link>http://blog.23snaps.com/happy-thanksgiving-5-facts-about-turkey-that-you-didnt-know-until-now/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 27 Nov 2014 18:00:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rachell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blog.23snaps.com/?p=39740097150</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Happy Thanksgiving everyone!
<p style="text-align: justify;">We hope that you're all having a great time celebrating the Holiday surrounded by great food and the people you love.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We thought, in honour of Thanksgiving, we'd round up some curious facts about the turkey, the big star of today's celebratory meal!</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">1 - In the United States, <strong>46 MILLION TURKEYS</strong> are eaten each <strong>THANKSGIVING</strong>, while only <strong>22 MILLION</strong> are eaten on Christmas Day and <strong>19 MILLION</strong> at Easter.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/ph-ho-maple-turkeysE.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740097179" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/ph-ho-maple-turkeysE.jpg" alt="ph-ho-maple-turkeysE" width="480" /></a>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://darkroom.baltimoresun.com/2012/11/thanksgiving-is-homegrown-in-howard-county/#1" target="_blank">Darkroom</a></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">2 - The average<strong> WEIGHT</strong> of a turkey purchased at Thanksgiving is <strong>15 POUNDS</strong>.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/250_crop_900x450_turkey-weightlifting.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740097173" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/250_crop_900x450_turkey-weightlifting.jpg" alt="250_crop_900x450_turkey-weightlifting" width="480" /></a>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://crossfitscranton.com/" target="_blank">Crossfitscranton</a></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">3 - The <strong>HEAVIEST</strong> turkey ever raised was <strong>86 POUNDS</strong>, about the size of a large <strong>DOG</strong>.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/dog_dressed_as_turkey_04.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740097174" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/dog_dressed_as_turkey_04.jpg" alt="dog_dressed_as_turkey_04" width="480" /></a>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://www.thatcutesite.com/dogs-dressed-as-turkeys.html" target="_blank">That Cute Site</a></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">4 - The <strong>MALE</strong> turkey is called a <strong>TOM</strong>. The <strong>FEMALE</strong> turkey is called a <strong>HEN</strong>. Toms have beards and black, hair-like feathers on their breast.</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/56434c22ed2faae8465d64357f423e72.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740097176" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/56434c22ed2faae8465d64357f423e72.jpg" alt="56434c22ed2faae8465d64357f423e72" width="289" /></a>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://www.pinterest.com/pin/129971139217739714/" target="_blank">Pinterest</a></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;">5 - <strong>BABY</strong> turkeys are called <strong>POULTS</strong> and they are tan and brown. Aren't they cute?!</p>
<a href="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1353607849640531.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-39740097180" src="http://blog.23snaps.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1353607849640531.jpg" alt="1353607849640531" width="480" /></a>
<i> Image Source: <a href="http://imgfave.com/view/2938302" target="_blank">ImgFave</a></i>

&nbsp;

Do you have any other interesting Thanksgiving turkey facts for us? We'd love to hear them!

=)

<i> Top Image Source: <a href="http://www.wallcrash.com/funny-turkey-live-phone-wallpaper/funny-turkey-live-phone-wallpaper-2/#main" target="_blank">Wall Crash</a></i>]]></content:encoded>
